<li>Requirement of ArcA for redox regulation in Escherichia coli under microaerobic but not anaerobic or aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22843529" target="_blank">22843529</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The activation of ArcA under aerobic conditions may be due to the fact that ArcA is a part of a two-component regulatory system that responds to the redox state of the quinone pool ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two-component systems generally allow rapid adaptation to environmental change ; thus , as aerobic respiratory conditions become less favourable , the process of ArcA activation through phosphotransfers ( luchi and Lin , 1992a , b ) allows a rapid response to the change in the cellular redox state , preparing the cell for the new conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , profound effects of the absence of ArcA were seen under conditions of oxygen-restricted growth : increased respiration , an altered electron ﬂux distribution over the cytochrome o - and d-terminal oxidases , and a signiﬁcant change in the intracellular redox state were observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12486057" target="_blank">12486057</a>]<br></li>
<li>This implies that the redox state of the ubiquinone pool is not a major factor in switching ArcA between active and inactive states under the conditions used here , but rather that ArcA activity decreases as aerobiosis increases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is possible that the different strains and growth conditions used in the two studies might contribute to differences in ArcA activity and ubiquinone/ubiquinol redox profiles .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lack of ArcA causes reduced stationary phase survival under glucose-starvation conditions , which was attributed to the deregulation of cellular redox balance and the uncontrolled drainage of the cells ' endogenous energy reserves ( Nystrom et al. 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20707865" target="_blank">20707865</a>]<br></li>
<li>The effect of ArcA and Fnr on the TCA cycle genes and the electron transfer chain genes under microaerobic conditions is interesting since it was previously found that ArcA and FNR regulators affect the succinate ﬂuxes as well as the redox potential ( as measured by the NADH/NAD ratio ) , under those + conditions ( Shalel-Levanon et al. , 2005a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>The production and uptake of acetate , one of the metabolic byproducts of E. coli under hypoxic conditions , is not predicted to be under the direct control of ArcA according to this and another genome-wide study with the same subject ( Salmon et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20707605" target="_blank">20707605</a>]<br></li>
<li>The requirement of ArcA for survival under these conditions was attributed to the minimization of oxidative damage caused by unchecked respiration and possibly to the regulation of the utilization of endogenous carbon reserves , such as membrane lipids ( Nystrom et al. 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20707865" target="_blank">20707865</a>]<br></li>
<li>The cyd and cyo operons encoding the quinol oxidases Cyo and Cyd which operate under aerobic or microaerobic conditions are subject to O2 regulation by ArcA and FNR ( Tseng et al. , 1996 ; Fu et al. 1991 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11931557" target="_blank">11931557</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcB/ArcA system is also known to activate several operons , such as cyd encoding the cytochrome d complex and pfZ encoding pyruvate formate lyase , under microaerobic-growth conditions ( 16-18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8226939" target="_blank">8226939</a>]<br></li>
<li>is required for the fully extended lifespan of the lipA and lpdA mutants ArcA is a transcription factor that suppresses the expression of genes involved in respiration and activates genes involved in fermentative metabolism , thus contributing to the adaptation of E. coli to hypoxic conditions ( Iuchi & Lin 1991 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20707865" target="_blank">20707865</a>]<br></li>
<li>The corresponding regulator is ArcA ( gene product of arcA ) , which acts as a repressor under such conditions ( Iuchi & Lin 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1854188" target="_blank">1854188</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcA protein of E. coli is a global transcription factor that mediates gene expression in response to changing redox conditions ( Lynch & Lin , 1996b ; Iuchi & Lin , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>The His - tagged ArcA protein was puriﬁed from IPTG-6 treated E. coli M15 cells transformed with pREP4 and pQE30ArcA by nickel chelate afﬁnity chromatography under denaturing conditions , and the protein was renatured by gradual removal of the denaturant ( urea ) by dialysis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>The instability of the phosphate link to ArcA under extreme conditions of pH was indicative of an aspartyl phosphate bond ( probably at either the conserved Asp-11 or Asp-54 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1512197" target="_blank">1512197</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dramatic effects with regard to the intracellular redox state ( NADH/NAD ratio ) under microaerobic conditions in a strain lacking ArcA allow us to conclude that ArcA is a microaerobic redox regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12486057" target="_blank">12486057</a>]<br></li>
<li>The double mutant , arcA cra , exhibited very low activities compared with either of the single mutants , showing that the combined effects of the Cra and ArcA proteins in wild-type cells are less than additive The fnr null mutation lowered cyd-lacZ fusion activity under stationary phase , microaerophilic conditions but increased this activity under logarithmic phase , anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is suggested FixK in R. meliloti , and the azurin genes that the cyd operon is activated by ( azu ) of Alcaligenes faecalis and A. deni - ArcA under microaerobic conditions trificans23 , which encode the blue-cop - and repressed by FNR under anaerobic per proteins thought to be involved in conditions , so that this dual control nitrite respiration and therefore likely allows cytochrome d oxidase synthesis to be induced anaerobically .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1957353" target="_blank">1957353</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activated ArcB undergoes a phosphorelay of His292 to Asp576 to His717 , and subsequently activates its cognate transcriptional-regulator ArcA by phosphorylating ArcA at Asp54 to repress genes contributing to aerobic metabolism ( e.g. citrate synthase and isocitrate lyase ) and activates genes necessary for anaerobic metab-olism ( e.g. pyruvate formate lyase and hydrogenase ) [ 23,25,30-34 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19715602" target="_blank">19715602</a>]<br></li>
<li>During anaerobic-growth , the regulator ArcA represses expression of enzymes involved in aerobic metabolism ( 27 ) and activates expression of pyruvate formate-lyase , hydrogenase 1 , and cytochrome d oxidase ( 9 , 25 , 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary ArcA is one of several transcription factors required for optimal anaerobic induction of the pyruvate formate-lyase ipff ) operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because the function of the PDH complex is adopted by pyruvate formate-lyase ( PFL ) under anaerobic conditions , it was anticipated that the two operons might exhibit reciprocal responses to the redox-responsive regulators , ArcA and FNR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8057842" target="_blank">8057842</a>]<br></li>
<li>Deletion of ArcA neither signiﬁcantly altered the in vivo activity of the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex and pyruvate formate lyase nor signiﬁcantly affected catabo-lism under fully aerobic and fully anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12486057" target="_blank">12486057</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of oxygen , ArcA is bound to its cognate sites acting to repress transcription of the fad regulon genes , even under non-inducing conditions ( without fatty acids ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is not surprising that ArcA , which is active under conditions of oxygen limitation , is an activator of moe operon transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11357510" target="_blank">11357510</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it appears that ArcA , either directly or indirectly , negatively regulates the transcription of the anaerobic b-oxidation pathway genes fadJ and fadI in the absence of oxygen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA regulates fumA and fumC at 0 % to 21 % oxygen concentration , and strongly represses the genes at 0 -- 4 % .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>The model presented here is supported by the following evidence : ( i ) FadR repression coincides with ArcA repression for the fatty acid metabolism under anaerobic conditions ; ( ii ) ArcA-P is a DNA-binding protein speciﬁc to the upstream of fad regulon genes involved in fatty acid metabolism of E. coli ; ( iii ) under anaerobic conditions , transcription of fad regulon genes is increased upon the inactivation of ArcA , whereas , under aerobic conditions , transcription of those genes is not affected by the inactivation of ArcA ; ( iv ) the fadR deletion affects both aerobic and anaerobic transcription of fad regulon genes ; and ( v ) under anaerobic conditions , the transcript levels of fad regulon genes are synergistically increased upon the deletion of both arcA and fadR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , a putative FIS binding site ( TTGCA-TATTTTTAACACAA , 236 to 18 ) lies within the fadBA Expression of fadL and fadD are additively repressed by FadR and ArcA under anaerobic conditions The weak effects of FadR inactivation on expression of fadL and fadD suggested that other regulatory proteins may be involved and thus we tested the effects of deletion of the genes encoding the other proteins proposed to-bind these promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23029459" target="_blank">23029459</a>]<br></li>
