<li>ArcA generally behaves as an anaerobic repressor , but in some cases it may activate anaerobic transcription ( luchi and Lin , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The residual anaerobic induction could be shown to be imparted by the transcriptional-regulator ArcA ; an arcA4 fnr double mutant was incapable of inducing pfl transcription anaerobically .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>The residual anaerobic regulation observed in an far mutant recently could be attributed to a second global transcriptional-regulator , ArcA ( Sawers and Suppmann , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genes and regulators responding to O2 and other acceptors FNR and ArcA , as shown earlier for NarL and NarP , control different sets of target genes Žreviewed in w4 ,5,9,11,12,44 x. FNR acts as the major regulator of anaerobic metabolism and ArcA as the regulator of aerobic metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9230919" target="_blank">9230919</a>]<br></li>
<li>TorC autoregulation is different from tor anaerobic control The torCAD operon is fully induced in anaerobiosis but , in contrast to all other known anaerobic respiratory systems , this control is mediated neither by FNR , a pleiotropic anae-robic regulator , nor by ArcA , a response-regulator involved in redox control of numerous genes ( Simon et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10411745" target="_blank">10411745</a>]<br></li>
<li>Abbreviations used : ArcA , anaerobic respiratory control ; FNR , fumarate and nitrate reductase regulator ; HMP , ﬂavohaemoglobin ; TMAO , trimethylamine N-oxide .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16417494" target="_blank">16417494</a>]<br></li>
<li>Remarkably , anaerobic control is mediated neither by FNR , the general anaerobic regulator , nor by ArcA , another anaerobic global regulator ( luchi and Lin , 1988 ; Pascal et aL , 1984 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8596446" target="_blank">8596446</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data indicate that both ArcA and FNR are essential for anaerobic activation of promoter 7 transcription , which suggests functional interaction between these proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note , however , that this group also includes sodA ( 6.7-fold induction ) , which is regulated by FNR and other transcription factors , and cyoA , which is known to be repressed by ArcA during anaerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16377617" target="_blank">16377617</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the factors controlling the anaerobic transcription of hya and hyb have not been completely established , since neither FNR nor ArcA could completely account for the anaerobic induction of these operons .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15659690" target="_blank">15659690</a>]<br></li>
<li>Woods and Guest ( 46 ) demonstrated that the fumB gene is elevated 4-fold during anaerobic fermentative growth , and Tseng ( 47 ) showed that both ArcA and FNR are responsible for this anaerobic activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12754220" target="_blank">12754220</a>]<br></li>
<li>The anaerobic fumarase , encoded by fumB , is known to be activated during anaerobic fermentative growth ( 50 , 51 ) , and Tseng ( 51 ) showed that both ArcA and FNR are responsible for this anaerobic activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results indicated that FNR is not directly responsible for the residual anaerobic repression , although it could still act in conjunction with ArcA , or function as an anaerobic repressor solely in the absence of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>FNR appeared not to function as an independent anaerobic repressor , but it could serve as an anaerobic repressor in the absence of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>This group also includes operons such as hybO that are thought to be repressed by ArcA during anaerobic-growth , so the effects of NarL at these promoters might again be direct , indirect ( via the ubiquinol pool ) , or both .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16377617" target="_blank">16377617</a>]<br></li>
<li>This pattern is similar to that of how ArcA achieves its activation of PgadE under anaerobic condition which is also through its interaction with the P3 and P1 promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , ndh expression was rapidly and strongly enhanced in the anaerobic to aerobic transition , which could be explained by ArcA , FNR and PdhR all repressing ndh expression under the initial anaerobic conditions followed by rapid de-repression upon introduction of oxygen , which inactivates ArcA and FNR , and causes pyruvate accumulation , by inhibition of pyruvate for-mate-lyase [ 20 ] , to inactivate PdhR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>This explanation of the asymmetry of the ndh transcript profiles in the transitions implies that the ndh transcript response in a pdhR mutant should resembl the wild-type for the anaerobic -- aerobic transition ( ndh repression is still relieved upon inactivation of ArcA and FNR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>By contrast , the ndh transcript abundance should decrease in aerobic -- anaerobic transitions of the pdhR mutant because there is no PdhR-mediated de-repression to counter-balance ArcA and FNR-mediated repression that occurs upon oxygen exposure .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>Tbe mid-volt potential for anaerobic respiration witb nitrate , +430 mV , is clearly not sufficient to allow ArcA to switch from an inactive state ( no repression of sdhC-lacZ expression ) to an active state ( repression of sdhC - / acZexpression ) , if it was sufficient , a partial derepression of sdhC-lacZ expression would be observed when the anaerobic electron acceptors of different mid-voit potentials are used .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>Assuming that P-galactosidase activity tmly reflects AcnA synthesis , it would appear that a c n A is a typical citric acid cycle gene , subject to catabolite and anaerobic repression mediated by the corresponding regulators , CRP and ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>This led us to ask how the H-NS mediated repression is replaced by the ArcA dependent activation during the transition of the facultative bacterium E. coli from its aerobic to anaerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two possibilities may explain the transition from H-NS mediated repression to ArcA mediated activation of gadE-mdtEF during the transition from aerobic to anaerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIGURE 6  ArcA antagonizes the H-NS mediated repression of gadE under anaerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>We found that unlike the regulatory patterns occurred during aerobic acid stresses , anaerobic activation of the gadE-mdtEF operon is primarily mediated by ArcA through its antagonization of the H-NS mediated repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , anaerobic activation of gadE-mdtEF through antagonizing the H-NS mediated repression by ArcA provides a regulatory model that is relevant to the dynamic lifestyle of the facultative bacterium E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together these results conﬁrmed that ArcA and MnmE are primarily responsible for the anaerobic activation of mdtEF .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the observed MnmE mediated anaerobic activation of gadE-mdtEF was not due to its potential effects on ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>If MnmE affects either the production or phosphorylation of ArcA ( which affects the regulatory activity of ArcA ) , mnmE should cause full or partial de-repression of these two promoters under anaerobic condition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , the residual anaerobic repression by nitrate and the repression by fumarate could be an indirect effect of ArcA , since the level of active ArcA is dependent on the respiratory state of the cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA mediates repression during anaerobic-growth ( 36 ) and probably with low aeration .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22636776" target="_blank">22636776</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , the significant level of FadL expressed under ArcA repression probably provides sufficient oleate transport to satisfy the poor catalytic activity of FadK with this substrate and allow the observed slow anaerobic-growth on oleate [ 35 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23029459" target="_blank">23029459</a>]<br></li>
<li>Future experiments must show why , in the long i ` usion -LCB- nuosgg ) , the anaerobic repression of nuo by ArcA and the nitrate stimulation by NarL is largely lost .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>The main effecf was an anaerobic repression by ArcA and a nitrate stimulation by NarL .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
