<li>These results indicate that ArcA directly represses the expression of fad regulon genes during anaerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>A 15.5-fold anaerobic lacks promoter P7 and sequences important for ArcA - induction of lac2 expression from the ARM1036A dependent regulation of expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , anaerobic ArcA regulation of expression was signiﬁcantly impaired .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data indicate that ArcA regulation requires P7 and that P7 or DNA sequences in the vicinity of P7 are involved in modulating anaerobic induction of pﬂ expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA and AppY antagonize IscR repression of hydrogenase-1 expression under anaerobic conditions , revealing a novel mode of O2 regulation of gene expression in Escherichia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25266384" target="_blank">25266384</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , the concentration of IscR , in addition to regulation by ArcA and AppY , is important for determining the anaerobic expression levels of PhyaA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is phenotypicaily similar to the effect of an arcA mutation on anaerobic pfl-lacZ expression ( see Fig. 4C ) ArcA and FNR regulation of pfi 739 740 G Sawers Table 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of nrdA was independent of ArcA ( Table 2 ) , but we found a signiﬁcant increase in the anaerobic stationary-phase expression of nrdA in the fnr mutant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12923108" target="_blank">12923108</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although FNR and ArcA are clearly implicated in the anaerobic regulation of hya , the level of anaerobic expression observed even in the arcA fnr double mutant was still greater than that found for aerobic-growth ( Table 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10537212" target="_blank">10537212</a>]<br></li>
<li>This was accomplished by the use of DNA microarrays to analyze gene expression profiles in E. coli cells cultured at steady-state growth rates under aerobic ( O2 ) or anaerobic ( O2 ) growth 84 This paper is available on line at http://www.jbc.org conditions and in cells cultured under anaerobic-growth conditions in the presence ( O , ArcA ) or absence ( O , ArcA ) of 2 2 the ArcA protein or in otherwise arcA and arcA isogenic strains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Identification of Differential Gene Expression Patterns Resulting from Two-variable Perturbation Experiments To identify the global changes and adjustments of gene expression patterns that facilitate a transition from aerobic to anaerobic-growth conditions and to determine the effects of genotype on these gene expression patterns , we analyzed E. coli gene expression profiles obtained from cells cultured under aerobic ( O ) or anaerobic ( O ) growth conditions 2 2 and under anaerobic-growth conditions in the presence ( O , 2 ArcA ) or absence ( O , ArcA ) of ArcA , the global regula-2 tory protein for anaerobic metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Apparently a portion of the ArcA protein can exist in a phosphorylated state during aerobic-growth conditions such that icd-lacZ expression remains partly repressed except when cells are grown on substrates such as acetate or succinate ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>This repression of mdh-lacZ expression by ArcA under aerobic conditions is thought to be caused by a fraction of the ArcA protein that exists in a partially phosphorylated state under these conditions ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592446" target="_blank">7592446</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , the lldPRD operon is proposed to be under the control of the global regulator ArcA , which binds to positions 14 to 3 with respect to the transcriptional start site , corresponding to the proposed P2 promoter , and represses the expression of this operon under anaerobic conditions ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18263722" target="_blank">18263722</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the expression of the cyd operon has been shown to be activated by ArcA during anaerobic as well as aerobic-growth ( 25 ) and to be repressed by Fnr during anaerobic-growth ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>This operon is induced under an-aerobic conditions in the presence of formate or fumarate , repressed in the presence of nitrate , and requires acidic pH , ArcA , and AppY for optimal expression ( 12 , 21 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702328" target="_blank">14702328</a>]<br></li>
<li>The effects of nitrate ( via NarL ) and anaerobic derepression ( ArcA dependent ) appeared to be additive , as shown by the high expression of nuoy ^ ^ / lB ' in the arcA background after anaerobic-growth with nitrate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results clearly demonstrate that ArcA represses expression of arcZ during anaerobic-growth , the expected condition for ArcA to be active .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>( B ) The ArcA regulon shows greater differential expression and greater consistency for the WT aerobic/anaerobic shift and in the comparison between aerobic WT and aerobic ECOM4LA , thereby suggesting that ArcA is active in ECOM4LA , even under aerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>The residual anaerobic repression suggests that other regulators may either repress acnA under anaerobic conditions ( especially in the absence of ArcA ) or activate a c n A expression under aerobic conditions both in the presence and absence of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>The apparent surprise is the stringent repression by ArcA seen under anaerobic conditions even in the absence of FadR because E. coli has a pathway to degrade fatty acids under anaerobic conditions [ 34 ] and low expression of FadD and FadL would seem likely to compromise function of the anaerobic pathway .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23029459" target="_blank">23029459</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression Pattern I : Decreased Expression during Anaerobiosis and Increased Expression in an ArcA Strain -- Among the 175 genes displayed in the clustering procedures described above , 37 showed decreased expression under anaerobic conditions due to regulation by ArcA ( Table I ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The arcA mutant , which is deﬁcient in the O2-responsive regulator ArcA ( 9 ) , showed only a twofold decrease in dcuC9-9lacZ expression under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10368146" target="_blank">10368146</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression Pattern IV : Increased Expression during Anaerobiosis and No Change in an ArcA Strain -- The six genes of this cluster ( Table IV ) showed elevated expression under anaerobic-growth conditions , but were not affected by deletion of the arcA allele .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>To explain the peak of cyd expression observed under microaerobic conditions , it was hypothesized that the two regulatory proteins act in competition at the cyd promoter and that under strictly anaerobic conditions the relatively weakly acting FNR protein out-competes the ArcA protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1957353" target="_blank">1957353</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other than its effect on the rpoS regulon , CsgD expression appears to regulate a subset of anaerobiosis-dependent genes , such as ompW and pﬂB , both induced in anaerobic conditions by FNR , either alone or in concert with ArcA ( 18 , 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this same report , FNR and IHF were reported to have roles as weak repressors under anaerobic conditions , and it was suggested that the effect of FNR may be indirect as a consequence of its role in regulating ArcA expression ( 30 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12754220" target="_blank">12754220</a>]<br></li>
<li>FnrS is involved in gene regulation after the shift from aerobic to anaerobic conditions , and its expression is activated by the transcription factors FNR and ArcA ( 20 , 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23980183" target="_blank">23980183</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , it was reported recently that ArcA and FNR repressed the expression of puuA when E. coli was grown under anaerobic conditions and that there are putative binding motifs of ArcA and FNR upstream of the open reading frame of puuA ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18495664" target="_blank">18495664</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rather , hya expression in S. enterica is regulated not by IscR or ArcA but , rather , by FNR under anaerobic conditions ( 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>is repressed by FNR and stimulated by ArcA under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9230919" target="_blank">9230919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of cyd is thus stimulated by ArcA under microaerobic conditions and repressed by FNR unde anaerobic conditions , resulting in a maximal expression under microaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11931557" target="_blank">11931557</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA alone appears to slightly repress PhyaA under anaerobic conditions , since a strain containing deletions of appY and iscR ( ArcA ) showed an intermediate expression level ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA and AppY had no effect on PhyaA expression under aerobic conditions , as expected ( Fig. 1C ) , since ArcA is not active aerobically and since AppY is poorly expressed under these growth conditions ( 1 , 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regarding ArcA , the effect of ArcA on ndh expression was studied under anaerobic conditions in LB medium which was supplied with 20 mM xylose ( Liu and De Wulf , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is possible that under our experimental conditions the effect of ArcA on ndh expression is negligible .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , FadR and ArcA seem to act synergistically in fadBA expression under anaerobic conditions in that loss of either repressor results in only a small ( 3 - to 4-fold ) increase in expression whereas loss of both repressors results in a 12-fold increase in expression ( Fig. 6B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20622065" target="_blank">20622065</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previous studies ( 5 , 31 ) showed that deletion of ArcA or AppY results in decreased expression of PhyaA under anaerobic conditions , which led to the hypothesis that ArcA and AppY activated PhyaA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , under anaerobic conditions , the expression of fadK is independent of FadR and ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the expression data , we saw that ArcA activation in ECOM4LA is likely responsible for the anaerobic phenotype under aerobi conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under aerobic conditions , ArcA + in a fur - fnr + background allowed for higher expression of sodA-lacZ ( compare NC439 vs. NC417 ; Table 3 , column 3 ) , while this was not the case in afur-fnr - background ( compare NC412 and NC419 ; Table 3 , column 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1565612" target="_blank">1565612</a>]<br></li>
<li>This proposal is consistent with the findings of our hemA-lacZ experiments , which indicate that ArcA is functioning to activate hemA expression during aerobic-growth conditions ( Table 3 ) while the major contribution of ArcA is seen anaerobically ( e.g. , best visualized in an fnr mutant , in which a 12-fold aerobic-anaerobic difference in hemA expression is seen ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previous studies with fnr ' strains indicated that CRP and ArcA have no direct effect on aerobic or anaerobic ndh expression , and that NtrA ( a ^ ) enhances ndh expression about two - to threefold , but only under aerobic conditions ( Spiro et ai .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8065261" target="_blank">8065261</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA functions as a repressor of gtA expression under each set of conditions : in a 1arcA strain , glA-lacZ expression was elevated to levels two - and eightfold higher than those seen in a wild-type strain under aerobic and anaerobic conditions , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>As another transcription regulator that controls fatty acid metabolism , ArcA has been shown to strongly ( > 20-fold ) repress the expression of 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase encoded by the fadB gene , and to weakly repress acyl-CoA dehydrogenase encoded by the fadE gene , under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA , when activated , can then bind to regulatory DNA sites to mediate both positive and negative control of gene expression ( 8 , 9 ) : cyo-ABCDE expression is repressed under anaerobic conditions , while cydAB expression is activated ( 3 , 4 , 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rationale of Regulatory Patterns Regulatory pattern I ( anaerobic repressed gene expression , i.e. decreased expression in the presence of ArcA ) ( Table I ) and pattern II ( anaerobic activated gene expression , i.e. increased expression in the presence of ArcA ) ( Table II ) are most easily reconciled with previous reports .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>not regulated by ArcA but expression is activated by a novel regulator , Arr , which responds to the presence of amino acids during anaerobic-growth ( Green & Guest , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9308170" target="_blank">9308170</a>]<br></li>
<li>Possibly , the differences in anaerobic expression of the hya operon in glucose medium and glycerol medium reflect differences in the levels of expression of the appY gene and/or in the levels of phosphorylation of the ArcA protein during anaerobic-growth in these two media .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071220" target="_blank">8071220</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , aerobic expression of the focA gene was reduced by the p6A mutation , as was the dependence on ArcA for anaerobic induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>whose expression is reduced by ArcA during anaerobic-growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Scheme for ArcA control of gitA gene expression in response to anaerobic cell growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>In an attempt to identify possible gene products involved in the tpx gene expression in response to oxygen availability , we measured expression levels of b - galactosidase activity under different conditions of aeration in a series of strains carrying mutations in the genes encoding known aerobic/anaerobic transcriptional-regulator proteins , ArcA and Fnr ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fumA gene transcription is positively regulated by Crp and repressed by ArcA and its expression is predominant under aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22513097" target="_blank">22513097</a>]<br></li>
<li>The second protein that regulates anaerobic gene expression is ArcA , which was identified as being necessary for repressing expression of the succinate dehydrogenase gene under anaerobic conditions ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>This anaerobic response is modulated by the ArcA protein , which functions as a repressor of mdh gene expression under both aerobic and anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592446" target="_blank">7592446</a>]<br></li>
<li>During an-aerobic cell growth conditions , this repression is optimal : under some conditions of aerobic cell growth , ArcA appears to still partially repress gene expression ( ca .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , these results show that gene expression changes are consistent with ArcA being active in ECOM4LA under aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>Global gene expression suggests that ArcA is active in ECOM4LA in aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary The ArcA and Fnr regulators of Escherichia coii , both of which are activated in anaerobic conditions , negatively regulate the sodA gene ( coding for manganese superoxide dismutase ) , but Fnr has no effect on anaerobic sodA expression in a \ arcAAfnr background ( Compan and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>The aerobic and anaerobic control of gltA4-lacZ expression is due primarily to the arcA gene product ( Table 4 ; Fig. 5 ) , whereas sdhCDAB gene expression is controlled by both ArcA and Fnr ( 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>The differences observed in tpx gene expression during aerobic vs. anaerobic-growth conditions were also reported for several tricarboxylic acid cycle genes , including sdhC , gltA , mdh , and for some respiratory pathway genes , frdABCD , dmsABC , narGHJI although the molecular basis for this ArcA - and Fnr-independent control is not understood ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>The extent of ArcA control of gitA and sdhCDAB gene expression under aerobic conditions is in marked contrast to the lack of Fnr control under the same conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dual control of tpx gene expression regulated by ArcA and Fnr proteins appears to provide maximum protection against the toxicity of oxidative-stress during aerobic and anaerobic-growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fnr represses sdhCDAB expression but oniy during anaerobic conditions , Wby does tbe aerobic/anaerobic control of sdhCDAB gene expression require two regulators , ArcA and Fnr ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to the aerobic increase in FumA and FumC activities , FumB is more abundant under anaerobic conditions and fumB gene expression requires ArcA and Fnr as transcriptional-activators ( Tseng , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , these Fnr-independent effects may result from altered ArcA activation , rather than from altered basal promoter activity , as none of the Fnr site mutations altered cyd ± lacZ expression in wild-type cells grown in the presence of oxygen , or in an anaerobically grown DarcA strain ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>The 12 - to 15-foid anaerobic induction ot pfi Q & r \ e expression is mediated by seven co-ordinately regulated promoters and induction requires the concerted action of the ArcA , Fnr and integration host factor ( IHF ) proteins ( Sawers and Bock , 1988 : 1989 ; Sawers and Suppmann , 1992 ; Sirko etat .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using arcA ~ iac transcriptionai and translational fusions , we show that arcA expression increases ( about fourfoid ) in anaerobiosis and that both Fnr and ArcA are required for fuil expression , in a \ fnr background , there ts no auto-activation , suggesting that ArcA enhances activation by Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine whether ArcA-dependent Fnr repression of sodA was produced by Fnr activation of arcA transcription , we have investigated the effects of Fnr and ArcA on arcA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Positive control ( i.e. , transcriptional activation of gene expression ) is provided by ArcA , while negative control ( i.e. , transcriptional repression of gene expression ) is due to the Fnr protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA appears to function as an anaerobic activator of hernA gene expression , while Fnr repression is dependent on ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the aerobic/anaerobic control of fumA and fumC gene expression involves ArcA repression at both the fumA and fumC promoters , while Fnr regulates fumC at a distance from the fumA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , these findings indicate that promoter P7 activity accounts for the anaerobic induction of expression in derivative ARM1036 and that ArcA mediates anaerobic induction when the Fnr-dependent P6 promoter is inactivated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>Maximal anaerobic induction of pfl expression depends heavily on the Fnr protein but in its absence ArcA is still functional in eliciting at least a partial anaerobic induction of expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Aerobic expression was also reduced partially by Fnr and ArcA control anaerobic induction of focA the p6-2 mutation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Fnr and ArcA proteins were not required for this anaerobic induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601854" target="_blank">7601854</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of the appY gene is induced immediately by anaerobiosis , and this anaerobic induction is independent of Fnr , and AppY , but dependent on ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>The anaerobic control of icd expression by ArcA and that by Fnr appear to occur relatively independently of each other .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Fnr protein is responsible for this anaerobic induction , but a twofold reduction in a AarcA background indicates that ArcA contributes to the activation of its own expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , ArcA was required for elevated P1 , P2 , P3 and P4 expression in the absence of Fnr ( Fig. 6 , compare lanes 7 and 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , these data indicate that Fnr and ArcA can act independently of each other to control cyo-lacZ expression , in contrast to the requirement of ArcA for Fnr control of cyd-lacZ expression ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fnr bound at the half-site upstream of P7 may function together with bound ArcA ( 5 ) to activate expression from the P7 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rather , it appears that both ArcA and Fnr can regulate pﬂ expression under particular circumstances in aerobically grown cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>In strains defective in ArcA and Fnr synthesis , expression was reduced both aerobically and anaerobically .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the Fnr and ArcA proteins appear to function independently of each other to control fumA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similarly , Fnr can function in mediating partial induction of expression in the absenoe of ArcA or IHF .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Aerobic expression was independent of ArcA and Fnr , but induction of cydDC by nitrate and nitrite was dependent on NarL and Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9335308" target="_blank">9335308</a>]<br></li>
