<li>Members of this class are NtrC and PhoB , other candidates are ArcA , OmpR and KdpE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7641688" target="_blank">7641688</a>]<br></li>
<li>227 OmpR ArcA VirG PhoP Va `` R PhoB CreB TctD KdpE kINnlaRgre .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8294007" target="_blank">8294007</a>]<br></li>
<li>Surprisingly , we also found that even in the absence of AppY and ArcA , wild-type IscR could not repress PhyaA anaerobically as well as an IscR mutant that lacked the Fe-S cluster or as well as wild-type IscR aerobically at the same protein concentrations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>The repression by IscR in the absence of either ArcA or AppY appears to be a direct result of IscR binding , since the increase in expression observed from a mutation that is known to disrupt the IscR binding site ( C-to-G mutation at position 50 in PhyaA [ PhyaA ( 50G ) ] ) ( 28 ) mimicked the increase in expression of the iscR strains ( Fig. 1B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , the decreased expression of PhyaA that arises when strains lack ArcA ( AppY and IscR ) or AppY ( ArcA and IscR ) is reversed by the further elimination of IscR from either strain ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although isolation of AppY will be required before we can elucidate how this protein inhibits IscR repression at PhyaA , the simplest explanation is that both AppY and ArcA block IscR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ability of ArcA and AppY to act as antirepressors of IscR repression of PhyaA depended on IscR levels , suggesting that IscR competes with ArcA and/or AppY for binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , while the role of AppY in preventing repression by IscR is unclear , the simplest model from the combined results is that both AppY and ArcA act as antirepressors , competing with the repressor IscR for binding to PhyaA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>thermore , by similarly increasing the levels of IscR in a strain lacking ArcA and AppY , we found that less IscR was required for repression anaerobically ( Fig. 3C ) than in strains containing AppY and ArcA ( Fig. 3B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , much greater repression was observed aerobically than anaerobically at the same concentrations of IPTG , consistent with direct IscR repression at PhyaA without competition from ArcA and AppY aerobically .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>In sum , we have found that a combinatorial strategy leads to ArcA and AppY overcoming IscR repression at PhyaA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>To understand the contribution of each DR in ArcA repression of icdA , they were mutated toward or away from 5 = - TGTTA-3 = ( Fig. 1C ) , the most conserved sequence within each ArcA DR element ( hereinafter referred to as the consensus ) and , based on the PhoB DNA cocrystal structure ( 15 ) , the region likely contacted by ArcA in the major groove .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Even were there a false signal of this kind , it is not clear why these functions would be essential -- unless they replace aerobic functions which ArcA , due to this false signal , now could not induce .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12706508" target="_blank">12706508</a>]<br></li>
<li>luchi , S. , and Lin , E.C.C. ( 1988 ) ArcA ( dye ) , a global regulatory gene in Escherichia coil mediating repression of enzymes in aerobic pathways .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8596446" target="_blank">8596446</a>]<br></li>
<li>As a working model , it is tempting to speculate that it is only when ArcA repression is relieved , i.e. when toxic oxygen derivatives are produced as byproducts of aerobic metabolism and iron becomes a threat , that Fur would start to play a role in regulating sodA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA and RssB are phosphorylated and cooperate to keep S levels low by repressing rpoS transcription and stimulating S proteolysis , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>levels increase as rpoS transcriptional repression by ArcA is relieved and S proteolysis is slowed down ( since the cellular level of phosphorylated RssB is limiting for the overall rate of S degradation ) ( Pruteanu and Hengge-Aronis 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test whether the enhanced repression of P1icdA with mutant ArcA binding sites is still dependent on phosphorylation , the aspartate residue at position 54 ( site of phosphorylation [ 19 ] ) in the chromosomal copy of arcA was mutated to yield either alanine or glutamate , preventing phosphorylation from ArcB ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>We expected ArcA ( D54E ) to similarly reduce the repression of P1icdA , since this substitution has previously been shown to prevent both phosphorylation from ArcB and binding to the pﬂ promoter ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Physiological signals integrated by the ArcB/ArcA/RssB phosphotransfer network rpoS transcriptional repression by ArcA and ArcB-medi-ated phosphorylation and activation of RssB and , there-S fore , proteolysis , cooperate to maintain low cellular S levels in rapidly growing cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>In conclusion , S accumulation in cells entering into starvation is likely to be controlled by the interference of oxidized quinones with ArcB autophosphorylation and , therefore , reduced phosphorylation of RssB and ArcA , which results in reduced S proteolysis and a relief of rpoS transcriptional repression ( Fig. 7B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>An autoregulatory loop : effects of ArcZ on ArcB and vice versa ArcB leads to the activation of ArcA ( measurable by increased repression of the ParcZ -- lac and of a Psdh -- lacZ fusion ; as expected , this is fully ArcA dependent ) , and therefore tighter repression of arcZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>During the switch to aerobiosis , it is unclear how stimulation of ArcB-ArcA is relieved when electron transport via the aerobic respiratory chain is still tumed off by ArcA repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the four repressing plasmids seem to activate ArcB signalling to ArcA , resulting in increased repression of arcZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>In those studies , evidence of both ArcA repression of rpoS transcription and ArcB stimulation of RpoS degradation was found .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA repression of ArcZ provides a third level of negative regulation , and our studies with arcA and arcZ mutations demonstrate that this regulation has a signiﬁcant effect on translation of RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>Another possibility is that the nitrate repression is an indirect effect of ArcA regulation , since the phosphorylation of the ArcA protein by ArcB presumably is dependent on the respiratory state of the cell ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071220" target="_blank">8071220</a>]<br></li>
<li>As activation by ArcA is maximal in microaerobiosis ( Tseng et al. , 1996 ) , we favour the hypothesis that ArcA anti-repression prevents H-NS control in microaerobiosis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the mutated PicdA-lacZ , transcription from PII was eliminated by removal of its − 10 element such that transcription repression of this PicdA-lacZ is exclusively ArcA dependent ( Park and Kiley et al. , unpublished work , pers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Once active , ArcA directly binds to the promoter regions of fad regulon genes , resulting in transcriptional repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>There is a physiological rationale for the repression of feaR by PhoB and ArcA : O2 is required for the catab-olism of monoamines , and H2O2 is a threat to membrane integrity during phosphate-starvation ( 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fact that ArcA still has a regulatory role in the absence of H-NS strongly suggests that , in addition to antagonizing H-NS repression , ArcA also directly activates cydAB transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>The addition of DR4 to the 3 = end disrupted promoter function , preventing assessment of ArcA repression ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The addition of ArcA caused marked repression of transcription from ssbP3 and weaker repression of transcription from ssbP1 and ssbP2 Fig. 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140472" target="_blank">16140472</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , if this argument holds , then a strain incapable of synthesizing ArcA should show stronger nitrate repression in rich medium than in minimal medium , which is not what is observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601827" target="_blank">7601827</a>]<br></li>
<li>As ArcA most often acts as a repressor , it is tempting to speculate that ArcA may exert its activation by relieving H-NS repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , we demonstrated that the ArcA dependent activation of the operon is through its antagonistic effect on the H-NS mediated repression of the operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results do not distinguish direct repression by ArcA from an indirect effect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , H-NS repression of these four promoters is antagonized by ArcA in the absence of oxygen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA was identified as the dominant repressor , with the major repression occurring at 0 -- 4 % oxygen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>Enhanced ArcA repression is still dependent on phosphorylation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several mechanisms are also possible to explain how ArcA relieves H-NS repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>Either of these mechanisms could account for the relief of H-NS repression by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , this effect may be indirect , since neither the phosphorylated or unphosphorylated form of ArcA protein bound to the oxyR promoter region 2 in vitro ( 23 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9324269" target="_blank">9324269</a>]<br></li>
<li>Electrophoretic mobility shift assays and DNase I protection assays indicate that where the phosphorylated form of the ArcA protein ( ArcA-P ) is expected to act as a transcriptional-repressor ( e.g. , of lctPRD and gltA-sdhCDAB ) , the effect is likely to be mediated by sequestration of cis-controlling transcriptional-regulatory elements .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lane 1 , purified ArcA ( 15 ng ) phosphorylated in vitro using carbamoyl phosphate ; lane 2 , dephosphorylated ArcA ( 15 ng ) ; lanes 3 -- 8 , extracts from cultures grown at 0 , 31 , 45 , 71 , 90 , and 109 % aerobiosis , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lanes 1 and 4 lack IscR or ArcA ; lanes 2 and 3 contain 800 nM and 400 nM phosphorylated ArcA , respectively ; lane 5 contains 800 nM as-puriﬁed IscR ; lane 6 is a Maxam and Gilbert A G ladder made from the same DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lanes 1 and 2 contain 800 nM and 400 nM phosphorylated ArcA , respectively ; lane 3 contains 200 nM as-puriﬁed IscR and 800 nM phosphorylated ArcA ; lane 4 contains 200 nM as-puriﬁed IscR ; lane 5 contains no protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Protein -- DNA interaction assays Electrophoretic mobility shift assays ( EMSA ) were performed in 20-µL reaction mixtures , including increasing amounts of purified ArcA protein ( previously phosphorylated ) and 25 ng of DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test whether IscR and ArcA can bind simultaneously , electrophoretic mobility shift assays were performed with radiolabeled hyaA DNA , IscR , and/or phosphorylated ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since only ArcA-P binds to the DNA and the extent of in vitro phosphorylation of ArcA by acetyl-phosphate has not been determined , the actual concentration of ArcA-P in this experiment could be lower than the total ArcA ( ArcA + ArcA-P ) in the reaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11357510" target="_blank">11357510</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , while chemical cross-linking studies indicate that phosphorylation of the His6-ArcA protein stimulates dimerization of the protein ( 34a ) , the effect appears to be insufﬁcient to explain quantitatively the large differences observed in the in vitro DNA binding properties of the His - ArcA and His-6 6 ArcA-P proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is possible that phosphorylation of the ArcA protein also facilitates cooperative interactions of mol-ecules bound to the DNA , as is apparent in the case of the NtrC protein ( see chapters 5 and 9 in reference 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>They reported 58 differentially expressed genes of operons under the direct control of ArcA as evidenced by the presence of a documented or putative DNA-binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interpretation of Clustering Results Although some of the genes or operons differentially expressed in the presence or absence of ArcA are expected to be affected only indirectly , others whose expression is directly regulated by ArcA should possess a DNA-binding site ( s ) upstream of their transcriptional start site ( s ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because the expression levels of the 40 genes of patterns III and IV were not affected by the presence or absence of ArcA , they are not expected to possess binding sites for this regulatory protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is unresolved whether isolated ArcA includes a small population of phospborylated molecules or whelher the non-phosphorylated form of the protein also binds DNA , The singfe , high-affinfty ArcA-binding region , termed A-3 , may be that primarily invoived in mediating tbe ArcA-dependenl induction of pfl operon expression in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding of ArcA to eitber of tbese sites could provide a plausible explanation for tbe ArcA-dependent repression of lacZ expression in the absence of IHF , Clearly , the inability of IHF to-bind to this construct will cause a significant alteration of the DNA topology at the promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA-phosphate binds to DNA upstream of moe Since ArcA was required for optimum expression of moeA-lacZ , the ability of the ArcA protein to-bind to the promoter DNA was investigated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11357510" target="_blank">11357510</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , the analysis of the promoter derivative iacî ing a functional IHF-binding site revealed , surprisingly , that ArcA can repress pff expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA-binding studies with puriﬁed ArcA will be required to conﬁrm the supposition that ArcA regulates hya expression directly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10537212" target="_blank">10537212</a>]<br></li>
<li>De-ﬁning how these ArcA cis-regulatory elements contribute to ArcA DNA binding and repression is critical to understanding how the ArcAB system coordinates this global reprogramming of transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , changes in ArcA DNA binding should change P1 repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>To examine how ArcA interferes with IscR repression of PhyaA , in vitro DNA binding experiments were carried out with isolated ArcA and IscR ( Fig. 2A and B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , competition between NarL and ArcA for their corresponding binding sites in the pﬂ promoter-regula-tory region would provide a simple explanation for the variable level of nitrate repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601827" target="_blank">7601827</a>]<br></li>
<li>( C ) Effects of muta - ( Continued ) Figure Legend Continued FIG 5 Phosphorylation dependence of ArcA repression of P1icdA in strains with strengthened ArcA binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , ArcA may preclude H-NS binding to this region , thus preventing repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>Phosphorylated ArcA ( ArcA-P ) antagonizes H-NS binding to gadE promoter , resulting in the relief of repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that , independent of the strength of the binding site , repression is largely dependent on the phosphorylated form of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The analysis of the effects of mutations eliminating individual DR elements suggests that DR1 and DR2 determine the overall strength of ArcA binding and that all three DR elements contribute to repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>In support of this competition model , electrophoretic mobility shift assays and DNase I footprinting showed that the ArcA and IscR binding sites overlap and that binding of ArcA and IscR is mutually exclusive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the DNase I footprint and electro-phoretic mobility shift assays presented in this study , we propose that ArcA antagonizes IscR repression by partially occluding IscR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNase I footprinting analyses involving NarL and the same 286-bp BssHII-BamHI moe promoter DNA as used for ArcA experiments were performed essentially as mentioned above with changes only in the binding conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11357510" target="_blank">11357510</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA binding assays were used to determine whether IscR and ArcA bind simultaneously to the hya promoter region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , ArcA and IscR appear to compete for binding to the hyaA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lower IscR levels also contribute to decreased IscR regula ¬ FIG 2 ( A ) DNase I footprinting of ArcA and IscR binding to the hyaA promoter region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Incubation with carbannoyl phosphate enhances the DNA-binding activity of ArcA Direct Incubation with a low-moleoular-weight phosphodonor such as acetyl phosphate or carbamoyi phosphate has been shown to produce an active form of several pro-karyotic DNA-binditig proteins ( Li etal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>CpxR shares homology with other two-component DNA-binding proteins , including OmpR and ArcA ( Dong et al. 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7883164" target="_blank">7883164</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fur and ArcA DNA-binding sequences were found to overlap considerably and competition experiments , in agreement with in vivo results , demonstrate that Fur and ArcA repression of sodA are mutually exclusive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , competition experiments show that Fur and ArcA binding to the sodA promoter are mutually exclusive and that ArcA can easily displace Fur , but not vice versa .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , competition experiments show that binding of Fur and ArcA are mutually exclusive and that ArcA binds to Fur-coated DNA with about the same efficiency as to naked DNA , whereas Fur does not bind readily to ArcA-coated DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Competition between the global regulators Fur and ArcA for binding to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19400769" target="_blank">19400769</a>]<br></li>
<li>When Fur and ArcA are both present , the protected region corresponds either to the Fur or to the ArcA footprint , but clearly never include both , excluding simultaneous binding of Fur and ArcA to sodA DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Oxygen and choline exert their control via the transacting DNA-binding proteins ArcA and BetI , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>Also , the footprints became somewhat extended witb high concentrations of phosphorylated ArcA , which perhaps indicates that either non-specific DNA-binding or oligomerisation is enhanced by phosphorylation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Phosphorylation of ArcA considerably enhanced its binding to DNA , while ArcA-phosphate exhibited an apparent dissociation value of approximately 0.1 mM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA phosphorylation initiates a change in oligomeric state , resulting in DNA binding ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is the first report of experimental evidence for specific binding of ArcA to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA-P denotes the phosphorylated ArcA protein which is the DNA binding species .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20622065" target="_blank">20622065</a>]<br></li>
<li>This assumes that the nonphosphorylated form of ArcA has a considerably weaker afﬁnity for binding to DNA than does the phosphorylated form .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592446" target="_blank">7592446</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our ﬁnding that an N-terminally His-tagged variant of ArcA failed to stabilize binding to DR3 suggests that the His tag speciﬁcally disrupts the mechanism needed to enhance the energetics of DR3 binding site occupancy .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Due to the overlap with the activating cAMP-CRP-binding site , phosphorylated ArcA would not only act as a `` classical `` repressor , but also as an antiactivator for cAMP-CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>As in the case of the lctP upstream region , while the binding of His6-ArcA to the glt-sdh fragment appeared to be nonspeciﬁc , the binding of His6-ArcA-P appeared to be speciﬁc and resulted in the formation of multiple discrete complexes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , it is not possible to locate potential ArcA-binding sites by sequence analysis , although it is presumed that dctA is directly repressed by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10482502" target="_blank">10482502</a>]<br></li>
<li>In a few cases , adjacent LexA sites are bound in a cooperative manner , further enhancing the sensitivity to changes in signal ( 36 ) , as hypothesized for the ArcA binding sites located upstream of acs and astC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The conﬁguration of the ArcA DR elements may also provide a mechanism for achieving a stepwise response to changes in O2 , as suggested for OmpR-P dimer binding to the ompF and ompC promoters in response to changes in osmolarity ( 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The bacterial response-regulator ArcA uses a diverse binding site architecture to regulate carbon oxidation globally .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659771" target="_blank">24659771</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , these results suggest that improving binding afﬁnity through the use of consensus DR elements disrupts the signal-dependent regulation of ArcA DNA binding , suggesting that the degeneracy of DR2 and DR3 is important for balancing anaerobic repression with O2-dependent relief of repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data suggest that for icdA , the arrangement of multiple DNA binding elements appears to be tailored to achieve both sufﬁcient DNA binding afﬁnity and repression by ArcA while maintaining O2-dependent regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The regulation of ArcA on flagellin is likely to be indirect , as we did not detect specific binding of recombinant ArcA protein to the upstream sequence of fliC ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19715602" target="_blank">19715602</a>]<br></li>
<li>The simplest interpretation of these results is that strengthening binding afﬁnity disrupts O2-dependent regulation of ArcA DNA binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA region up to base pair - 2 7 7 is required for regulation by Oo and nitrate and fhe franscriptional reguiators ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>The finding that binding ability was retained after gel filtration only in the fraction containing high-molecular-weight complexes , suggests that ArcA In crude extracts aggregates as an homo - or heteropolymer favouring binding to DNA Footprints were obtained with crude extracts prepared in conditions ( aeroblosis ) \ n which ArcA is inactive in vivo on sodA ( Compan and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
