<li>These results suggested that sodA repression is partially mediated by Fnr and that increased levels of Fnr ( due to the presence of a multicopy plasmid bearing the fnr + gene ) can partially ( -50 % ) substitute for the absence of Fur , ArcA , or both .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1565612" target="_blank">1565612</a>]<br></li>
<li>During a study of sodA regulation , we noticed that Fnr repression of sodA was at least partially ArcA dependent ( Compan and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results Fnr modulates ArcA-dependent regulation of the sodA and sdh genes In studies of MnSOD reguiation several observations suggested that Fnr repression of the sodA gene was at least partly indirect and mediated by ArcA : a A ^ nr mutation had no effect in a AarcAAfur background ( Fig. 1 ) ; and , more strikingly , Fnr repression was not completely abolished in constructs in which the putative Fnr-binding sites were destroyed ( Compan and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , ArcA repression of fumA and fumC at various oxygen concentrations was found to be stronger than that of Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>As P1 , P3 and P4 are extremely sensitive to Fnr repression , we propose that the activity of these promoters may peak only under the narrow window of oxygen tensions in which ArcA is active , but Fnr is not .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulators such as ArcA , Fur , and Fnr would be found in much lower concentrations in the cell ; thus it is not surprising that their binding activities are not evident in cell-free extracts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7862094" target="_blank">7862094</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the event that Fnr repression resulted from interaction with RNAP , Fnr binding or activity would have to be directly or indirectly modulated by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the ArcB/ArcA and Fnr systems both come to play anaerobically , Fnr may sense the redox potential , whereas ArcB probably senses cellular concentrations of me-tabolites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8132465" target="_blank">8132465</a>]<br></li>
<li>Data from Cotter and Gunsalus ( 1992 ) showing that fnr transcription is not activated by ArcA seem to exclude an indirect effect mediated by Fnr , It is possible that there is an ArcA feedback loop , but only when a threshold concentration of ArcA protein is reached .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Compan , I. , and Touati , D. ( 1994 ) Anaerobic activation of arcA transcription in Escherichia coll : roles of Fnr and ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>Molecular Microbiology ( 1994 ) 11 ( 5 ) , 955-964 Anaerobic activation of arcA transcription in Escherichia coli : roies of Fnr and ArcA Ines Compan and Danlele Touati * Institut Jacques Monod , CNRS , Universite Paris 7 , 2 place Jussieu , 75251 , Pahs , Cedex 05 , France .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>We first assess whether another gene negatively reguiated by ArcA , ( sdh ) ( luchi and Lin , 1988 ) , is regulated by Fnr in an ArcA-dependent manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>This led to the hypothesis that Fnr activates arcA transcription and prompted us to examine the effect of fnr mutations on another ArcA repressed gene , sdh , coding for succinate dehydrogenase ( luchi and Lin , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Clearly , il will be necessary to examine the occupancy of site A-1 by ArcA in the presence of RNA polymerase and Fnr before any speculation can be made as to the physiological relevance of this binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Determining how ArcA , Fnr , IHF and RNA polymerase bind to their respective recognition sequences in the presence of the other proteins will obviously bring us a step further towards achieving this objective .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The focA ± pfl operon is also co-ordinately regulated by ArcA and Fnr ( although both proteins act as activators ) and is also transcribed from multiple ( seven ) promoters ( Sawers and BoÈck , 1989 ; Sawers , 1993 ; Drapal and Sawers , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the sucABCD genes are negatively regulated by both the ArcA and Fnr proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209026" target="_blank">9209026</a>]<br></li>
<li>The number of genes found to be regulated both by ArcA and Fnr is growing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>The major cydAB promoters , P1 and P2 , are regulated by ArcA and Fnr independently of each other .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>Certain genes are regulated by both ArcA and Fnr ( Fu et ai , 1991 ; Cotter and Gunsalus , 1992 ; Sawers and Suppmann , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>sodA belongs to the ArcA moduton ( Tardat and Touati , 1991 ) and is also negatively regulated by Fnr ( Hassan and Sun , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the corresponding genes are anaerobically induced , this induction is reported to be mainly Fnr , rather than ArcA dependent ( 11 , 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996819" target="_blank">14996819</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobically Fnr/ArcA activate the pff operon encoding pyruvate-formate lyase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412675" target="_blank">8412675</a>]<br></li>
<li>This control is mediated by the ArcA and Fnr proteins ( Gennis and Stewart , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16187334" target="_blank">16187334</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobic induction was dependent on both ArcA and Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobic induction is mediated by the ArcA and Fnr transcription factors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8709852" target="_blank">8709852</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the electron transfer chain genes no signiﬁcant effect of ArcA and Fnr was observed on nuoA , ndh , and ubiE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that under our conditions the ArcA has a negative effect on nuoA while Fnr has a positive effect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that under these conditions ArcA has a negative effect on gltA while Fnr has a slightly positive effect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that the negative effect of ArcA and Fnr on cyoA is not additive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140031" target="_blank">16140031</a>]<br></li>
<li>This , however , should not reverse the autoregulatory effect of ArcA , and it would not account for the Fnr modulation of ArcA regulation of sodA and sdh that we observed in anaerobiosis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>There are also dual effects of Fnr and ArcA which can not be completely explained by arcA regulation and suggest functional Fnr-ArcA interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus Fnr regulation of sdh is mediated by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Proposed model for regulation of the sdhCDAB and sucABCD genes by the ArcA , Fnr , and IHF proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209026" target="_blank">9209026</a>]<br></li>
<li>Experimenls are in progress to identify the enhancer-like element as well as to locate the sites for ArcA and Fnr regulation of the sdhCDAB genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possible explanation for this result is that as a result of the Fnr-2 mutation , Fnr no longer can bind to this sequence , which consequently affects the interaction of ArcA with the P7 regulatory sequences .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>model , invoking Fnr and ArcA as independent repressors , deserves to be reviewed in the light of the data collected from our studies of sdh and lct .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8132465" target="_blank">8132465</a>]<br></li>
<li>This indicates that ArcA activation is not absolutely dependent on Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that ArcA co-operates with Fnr in Pa activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>SJP33 although it is still ArcA - and Fnr-dependent ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA autoactivation thus appears to require Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA is less sensitive , while Fnr is more sensitive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
