<li>Both ArcA and Fnr proteins are synthesized in aerobiosis and activated in anaerobiosis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>aerobiosis , activated by ArcA and repressed by Fnr in anaerobiosis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>The aerobic role of ArcA , if any , seems to be dependent on the absence of Fur , and on whether Fnr is present or absent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1565612" target="_blank">1565612</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using arcA-lacZ transcriptional and translational fusions , we show that Fnr and ArcA activate transcription of arcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the absence of Fnr , ArcA was not able to induce transcription from P ^ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Whereas the fumA promoter is regulated by both Fnr and ArcA , transcription from the fumC promoter is regulated by ArcA and SoxR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>During fermentation , E. coli uses two global transcription factors , ArcA and Fnr , to regulate its metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcA and Fnr proteins are negative regulators of cyo-ABCDE transcription ( 1 , 3 , 4 , 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
<li>The action of many global transcription factors such as ArcA , Fnr , CRP , and IHF commonly involved both NADH and ATP , whereas others responded to either ATP or NADH .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20299454" target="_blank">20299454</a>]<br></li>
<li>Global transcription factors such as ArcA , Fnr , IHF , Fur , and CRP respond to both NADH and ATP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20299454" target="_blank">20299454</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this paper we report both in vivo and in vitro studies that suggest that the mechanism of Cra action depends both on Fnr and ArcA in opposing ways : Fnr is required for the Cra response , while ArcA counteracts it .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
<li>Remarkably , in contrast to all other known anaerobic respiratory systems , this control is mediated neither by the Fnr protein , the general anaerobic regulator ( 33 ) , nor by the ArcA protein ( 14 , 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8083154" target="_blank">8083154</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Fnr protein is required for Cra-mediated transcriptional control , but the ArcA protein antagonizes the response to Cra .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
