<li>Effect oMnr and arcA mutations on the expression of arcA-lac operon and protein fusions Fnr could modulate ArcA regulation of sdh and sodA either by affecting ArcA production or by interaction with ArcA itseif , as suggested by Sawers and Suppmann ( 1992 ) in a study of the regulation of the pfl gene by ArcA and Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , we believe that instead there is a functional interaction between Fnr and ArcA proteins , as in the dual Fnr and ArcA regulation of the pfl gene ( Sawers and Suppmann , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>The two global regulatory proteins ArcA and Fnr negatively regulate many of the TCA cycle genes in response to anaerobiosis ( 10 , 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several genes in E. coli are controlled cooperatively by both Fnr and ArcA , and in some cases the effects of these two regulatory proteins can not be explained by simple additive effects [ 6 , 10 , 20 , 31 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since a four - to ﬁvefold difference in both fumA-lacZ and fumC-lacZ expression was observed in response to oxygen availability , we examined whether the ArcA or Fnr regulatory protein was involved in this control as shown for other genes in E. coli ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>In Escherichia coli two global transcriptional-regulatory proteins , Crp and Cra , are known to control transcriptional responses to carbon availability [ 28 , 30 ] , while two other global regulators , Fnr and ArcA , control gene expression in response to oxygen availability [ 14 , 15 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dual pattern of hemA gene regulation by the Fnr and ArcA regulatory proteins is similar to that seen for the genes for cytochrome d oxidase in E. coli ( Table 3 ) , where Fnr functions to repress cydAB gene expression while ArcA somehow functions to activate their expression ( 6 , 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of the arcA and fnr gene products on sdhC-lacZ expression As a 10-fold difference in scy/7C - / acZ expression occurred in response to O ^ availahiiity , we tested the effect of the two known aerohic/anaerobic regulatory proteins , Fnr and ArcA , in this process .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the ArcA and/or the Fnr proteins are known to regulate several TCA cycle genes , including the sdhCDAB , mdh , gltA , acnA , and fumAC genes , in E. coli in response to anaerobiosis ( 6 , 8 , 16 -- 19 , 27 ) , we examined the effects of arcA and fnr gene deletions on sucA-lacZ and sdhCDAB-sucA-lacZ expression ( Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209026" target="_blank">9209026</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the ArcA and Fnr proteins are known to regulate a number of E. coli genes in response to anaerobiosis , we examined the effect of deleting each regulatory gene on gltA-lacZ expression ( Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , even moderate up-regulation of ArcA ( as observed in stationary-phase cells , see Fig. 6B ) should result in down-regulation of RssB activity and , therefore , S stabilization ( Fig. 6C ; for further discussion , see below ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our third attempt to gain a mechanistic insight into the regulation of lifespan by ArcA and Acs in the lipA strain was based on the published observation of a time-dependent increase in the amount of protein carbonyls during the stationary phase incubation of a wt population ( Dukan and Nystrom , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20707605" target="_blank">20707605</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that ArcA , either directly or indirectly , reduces fatty acid transport in the absence of oxygen through the repression of fadL and fadD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that ArcA , either directly or indirectly , represses the b-oxidation pathway in the absence of oxygen , through the negative regulation of fadE , fadB , fadA and fadH .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of oxygen , the oxygen-sensitive global regulators ArcA and FNR mediate the repression of many TCA promoters , but most dramatically the sdh-suc operon , which encodes SDH , KDGH , and the SCSC ( 104 , 105 , 170 , 293 , 335 , 339 , 406 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15755952" target="_blank">15755952</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , we have investigated the regulation of fatty acid metabolism by oxygen , and found that fatty acid transport and degradation is repressed by ArcA in the absence of oxygen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this investigation we dem-onstrate that regulation of bet by choline , oxygen , and osmotic stress is mediated by three separate mechanisms ; i.e. , BetI , ArcA , and an as yet unidentiﬁed osmotic signal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in the absence of glucose , ArcA and Fis are the most plausible candidates for mediating the co-regulation of lipoamide dehydrogenase and 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase synthesis via the respective lpd and sdh promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results support the view that co-regulation of the lpd and sdh promoters is mediated primarily by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was thus concluded that the co-expres-sion of lipoamide dehydrogenase and 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase involves co-regulation of the lpd and sdh promoters , mediated primarily by ArcA and an ill-de cents ned CRP-independent mechanism of glucose repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , ArcA regulation shows a strong dependence on IHF , indicating that IHF is necessary to allow ArcA to engage in transcriptional activation of this promoter system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the case of glpD , besides regulation by GlpR , the promoter is subject to regulation by cyclic AMP-CRP and by the ArcA / ArcB systems ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8955388" target="_blank">8955388</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we demonstrate that ArcA and ArcB mediate this residual transcriptional activation of the pfl operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this case , microaerobic activation is mediated by ArcA , P located at 295 relative to the transcript start .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11169114" target="_blank">11169114</a>]<br></li>
<li>To investigate ArcA regulation of the b-oxidation pathway , qPCR was used to measure transcript levels of fadE , fadB , fadA and fadH in the wild type , DarcA , DfadR and DarcA / DfadR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the ChIP results , and the transcript level of fadK in the wild type and DarcA mutant , indicate that its transcription is independent of ArcA regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA can positively or negatively regulate transcription of aerobic enzymes and has been demonstrated to control the resistance of E. coli to specific dyes [ 43 ] , presumably through regulation of envelope proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18824089" target="_blank">18824089</a>]<br></li>
<li>If this extra regulatory loop is conﬁrmed , it would suggest that not only do ArcA and ArcB negatively regulate RpoS , but RpoS participates in the negative regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>In conclusion , our results add the regulation of stationary phase heat-shock resistance to the cellular phenotypes regulated by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20707605" target="_blank">20707605</a>]<br></li>
<li>For some of them an oxygendependent regulation was previously reported : TalA and AcnA are negatively regulated by ArcA ( 51 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17015655" target="_blank">17015655</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobic regulation of the cyx-appA operon by ArcA and AppY .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>A different pattern was found in the anaerobic regulation of the acid phosphatase operon , suggesting that here ArcA and AppY act coordinately in activating the anaerobic transcription of the cyx-appA operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>This may be due to the up-regulation of arcA and its gene product ArcA , since cydB operon is under the positive control , while cyoA is under negative control of ArcA ( Additional file 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19055729" target="_blank">19055729</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests a negative role for ArcA in regulation of the hyb operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10537212" target="_blank">10537212</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , this suggests there is mutual negative regulation of arcB and arcZ RNAs , and this is ArcA independent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>Oxygen regulation by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>Functionally , the purpose for this regulatory feedback loop may be to provide a homeostatic regulation of the ArcA/ArcB regulon : when ArcZ is highly produced ( aerobic-growth ) , it represses ArcA activation by downregulating the levels of ArcB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>To further validate the activation of ArcA in ECOM4LA during aerobic-growth , we looked at genes previously identiﬁed as direct targets of ArcA regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA was reported to be necessary for the ROS resistance of Haemophilus influenzae due to its regulation of Dps , a ferritin-like small protein that was previously reported to be involved in ROS resistance of Salmonella [ 39,47 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19715602" target="_blank">19715602</a>]<br></li>
<li>For some genes , the observed changes in protein levels were consistent with known transcriptional regulation , such as ArcA activation of the operons encoding yccB and ybgT .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19734316" target="_blank">19734316</a>]<br></li>
<li>, B-Galactosidase specific activity ( 28 ) from a pfl-lacZ fusion was determined for cells grown aerobically ( solid bars ) , anaerobically ( open bars ) , or anaerobically with pyruvate ( stippled bars ) in rich media with the following strains : wt ( wild type ) , parent , RM123 ; himD , IHF - , RM444 ; frzr , FNR - , RM135 ; arcA , ArcA - , RM320 ; fnr himD , FNR - IHF - , RM324 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8376324" target="_blank">8376324</a>]<br></li>
<li>aerobic to anaerobic anaerobic to aerobic ArgR CysB BirA DgsA MalT GadW MetJ NikR OxyR SoxR SoxS DcuR CueR FadR HcaR NtrC PhoB PurR SgrR TdcA TrpR ZraR ArcA CpxR CRP CusR FhlA Fis FNR Fur H-NS IHF IscR Lrp ModE NarL NrdR PdhR FlhDC GlcC EvgA GadX LeuO PspF RbsR steady states Figure 3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>Part of the reason may be explained as follows : In the cultivation of cyoA and cydB mutants , cAMP-Crp was down-regulated , where this caused mlc gene to be down-regulated , which caused ptsG and ptsH genes to be up-regulated as seen in Figure 2e , where ptsG is also under control of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21272324" target="_blank">21272324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , to determine whether the observed asymmetry of the ndh response could be accounted for by changes in the activities of ArcA and FNR , a dynamical model was developed based on high-resolution RT-PC data for a training set of genes that were either ArcA - ( hypB and icd ) or FNR - ( dmsB , hybO ) regulated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that we might expect the total number of genes directly activated or repressed by ArcA to be in the range of 290 genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Liu and De Wulf identified a total of 138 genes as being activated in the presence of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , as suggested previously by us ( 1 ) and Liu and De Wulf ( 22 ) , the total number of genes directly activated or repressed by ArcA and FNR is likely to be much higher than documented previously .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , most of the genes in group III are repressed by the O2-sensing system mediated by ArcA ( 49 , 70 ) , and although not directly demonstrated , the data in this paper suggest that these genes can also be repressed by FNR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15659690" target="_blank">15659690</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the transcription factor MarA is not directly regulated by FNR or ArcA , four genes that are activated by MarA ( acnA , fumC , sodA , zwf ) are repressed by ArcA and/or FNR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23980183" target="_blank">23980183</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , all the fad genes repressed by FadR are also repressed by the ArcA transcription factor ( encoded by arcA ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23026122" target="_blank">23026122</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA can therefore function as an activator and as a repressor , and it is particularly interesting that ArcA regulates quite distinct sets of genes in response to signals from different sensors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1957353" target="_blank">1957353</a>]<br></li>
<li>It seems likely that a subset of genes that have been assigned to the ArcA/ArcB regulon are in fact indirectly regulated by ArcA , through ArcZ , but the complexity of the effects of ArcA , RpoS , and the apparent broad effects of ArcZ leave this as an interesting future direction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>Of these 37 genes , 10 have been reported to be directly regulated by ArcA ( 6 ) , and 27 are newly discovered genes that are regulated either directly or indirectly by this global regulatory protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobically , the intracellular concentration of active FNR becomes suficient to allow occupation of the FNRII site by displacing ArcA , and thereby inhibit the transcription activation mediated by the FNR dimer bound at FNR I .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11932447" target="_blank">11932447</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobically , the intracellular concentration of active FNR is now sufﬁcient to-bind at the FNR II site by displacing ArcA and thereby inhibit the transcription activation mediated by the FNR dimer bound at FNR I .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11932447" target="_blank">11932447</a>]<br></li>
<li>When iron becomes scarce , Fur becomes inactive , resulting in derepression of sodA transcription ; however , only under conditions in which FNR and ArcA are inactive ( i.e. in presence of O2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20075074" target="_blank">20075074</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with this hypothesis , growth in the presence of pyruvate or under microaerobic conditions elevates the level of YﬁD ( 50 , 290 ) , while the pyruvate-sensitive regulator PdhR and the ox-ygen-sensitive global regulators FNR and ArcA control yﬁD transcription ( 290 , 476 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15755952" target="_blank">15755952</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has recently been shown that , under anaerobic-growth conditions , Fpg activity increases in strains deﬁcient in the global regulators Fur , FNR , and ArcA ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10400579" target="_blank">10400579</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , the regulatory outcome is essentially reciprocal in that FNR usually activates transcription , whereas ArcA generally acts as a negative regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20075074" target="_blank">20075074</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of yﬁD as monitored by the yﬁD : : lac reporter fusion pGS1000 in the presence or absence of the transcription factors FNR , ArcA and PdhR , and the effect of acidity on the activity of these regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11932447" target="_blank">11932447</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other studies have shown that ArcA functions to activate cy-dAB transcription as oxygen becomes limiting ( 19 , 20 ) , whereas FNR is required for repression when the oxygen tension is decreased further ( 18 , 21 , 22 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12754220" target="_blank">12754220</a>]<br></li>
<li>Subsequent studies have shown that ArcA functions to anti-repress cydAB transcription when oxygen is limiting ( 46 ) , whereas FNR is required for repression when the oxygen tension is decreased further ( 14 , 17 , 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicate that repression by nitrate is independent of the three transcription factors ArcA , IHF , and FNR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601827" target="_blank">7601827</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nitrate repression is independent of IHF , FNR , and ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601827" target="_blank">7601827</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was anticipated that nitrate repression would not show a dependence on the presence of ArcA , FNR , or IHF , which proved to be the case .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601827" target="_blank">7601827</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the roles of FNR and ArcA in mediating the changes in transcript profiles necessary for adaptation to growth at different oxygen availabilities are well established ( see above ) , the consequent changes in physiology are expected to modulate the activities of other transcription factors that respond to specific metabolic signals that are affected by oxygen availability .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>Example of interactions between direct and indirect effects on transcription of narG ( encoding the membrane-associated nitrate reductase ) and cyo ( encoding a cytochrome oxidase ) because of ArcA , FNR , nitrate , oxygen , and changes in the redox state of the ubiquinone : ubiquinol pool .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16377617" target="_blank">16377617</a>]<br></li>
<li>There are no clear FNR or ArcA sites in front of dmlA , supporting the view that the effects of FNR , ArcA , and oxygen are indirect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20233924" target="_blank">20233924</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicated that excess putrescine is appropriately catabolized by products of the puu gene cluster that are regulated by ArcA , FNR , and PuuR to decrease the toxicity of putrescine and to utilize putrescine as both nitrogen and carbon sources .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18495664" target="_blank">18495664</a>]<br></li>
<li>These confirmed that the acnA gene resembles other citric acid cycle genes in being positively regulated by the CAMP-CRP complex and negatively regulated by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>The acnA gene is positively regulated by Crp , SoxRS , FNR and repressed by ArcA [ 59 ] , whereas acnB is positively regulated by CRP and negatively regulated by ArcA , FruR and Fis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22513097" target="_blank">22513097</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fumB gene is positively regulated by FNR , ArcA , Crp and Fur and negatively by Fis and NarL .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22513097" target="_blank">22513097</a>]<br></li>
<li>The modelled behaviours of ArcA and FNR were validated by direct measurements of the abundance of phosphorylated ArcA ( figure 5a , diamonds ) and by quantifying the transcript generated from activation of the synthetic FNR-dependent promoter FF-41 .5 ( figure 5b , dashed lines ) during the transitions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>The complete dependence of promoter 7 activity on both functional FNR and ArcA proteins was demonstrated in a primer extension experiment .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>The influence of CRP on the transcriptome progressively increased with increased aerobiosis , whereas the activities of ArcA , FNR , IHF and Lrp decreased as aerobiosis increased .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22870390" target="_blank">22870390</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although FNR is a direct O2 sensor , ArcA primarily responds to the redox status of the quinone pool and the accumulation of fermentation products , such as NADH and D-lactate ( 31 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16857675" target="_blank">16857675</a>]<br></li>
<li>For some target genes , FNR is the only regulator , whereas most are regulated coordinately by FNR and the regulators ArcA , NarL , NarP ( nitrate/nitrite regulation ) , Fur ( Fe regulator ) , SoxRS and Q ( regulation by O2̇ ¯ ) , LexA ( SOS regulation ) , or CRP ( glucose regulation ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8588737" target="_blank">8588737</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , open complex formation in the presence of RNA polymerase , which is an indication for active FNR and transcriptional activation , is stimulated by Fe ( II ) Most of the FNR-dependent promoters are regulated by FNR in cooperation with other regulators such as NarL , NarP ( nitrate regulation ) , ArcA , Fur ( ferric uptake regulation ) , or CRP ( cyclic AMP receptor protein , glucose repression ) ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8588737" target="_blank">8588737</a>]<br></li>
<li>The roles of the global transcriptional-regulators , ArcA , FNR , CRP , and RpoS , in the regulation of dctA transcription were investigated by studying the appropriate regulatory mutants .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10482502" target="_blank">10482502</a>]<br></li>
