<li>It currently assumed that ArcA also is a sequence-specific DNA-binding protein ( 17 ) and that it interacts with DNA in the pfl regulatory region , but its recognition sequence remains to be elucidated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8376324" target="_blank">8376324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , these data demonstrate that phosphorylated ArcA directly binds to two specific sites located upstream and immediately downstream of the rpoSp1 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIG 4 DNase I footprinting of ArcA binding to the icdA promoter region containing four DR elements .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNase I footprinting analysis revealed that ArcA interacts with two sites in the rpoSp1 region in a phos-phorylation-dependent pattern ( Fig. 3B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>The rpoSp1 promoter region contains two ArcA-binding sites , which are occupied by phosphorylated ArcA ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is possible that the different strains and growth conditions used in the two studies might contribute to differences in ArcA activity and ubiquinone/ubiquinol redox profiles .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , the majority of ArcA binding sites contain an additional one to three DR elements spaced by approximately one to two turns of the B-form DNA helix ( 11-bp or 22-bp CTC spacing ) from the minimal two DR sites ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>In either scenario , the predominance of three DR sites with 11-bp CTC spacing between each DR in the E. coli genome , together with our previous ﬁnding that ArcA-P did not bind to a predicted DR3 element in which the CTC spacing was separated by an additional bp ( 4 ) , suggests that protein-protein interactions between correctly spaced subunits is important for cooperative ArcA binding to multiple DRs. Because the C-terminal domain of ArcA binds as a dimer to two adjacent DRs , one can envision that binding of an ArcA-P dimer to DR1 and -2 stabilizes a second dimer or a monomer via protein interactions with DR3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>This latter result indicated that the phosphorylation of ArcA via His717 depended on the presence of His292 and Asp576 and that the phosphorelay involved an intermolecular reaction between different ArcB domains , in agreement with the results of our previous in vitro study ( 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10851007" target="_blank">10851007</a>]<br></li>
<li>A search using program PLsearch and alignment using program LOCAL revealed a second domain of about 120 amino acid residues in the C-terminal region that shows homology with the regulator proteins of two-com-ponent systems ( Fig. 6 ) , such as PhoB -LCB- Makino ef ai , 1986a ) , ArcA ( Dye ) ( Drury and Buxton , 1985 ) , Orf2 of the phoM operon -LCB- Amemura ef ai .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2201868" target="_blank">2201868</a>]<br></li>
<li>D-Lactate inhibits the phosphatase activity that re - moves phosphoaspartate groups from the receiver module in ArcB , and the associated increase in phos - phorylation of this module leads to an activation of transphosphorylationof subsequently added phospho - histidine groups on ArcBto the receiver moduleof ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8226939" target="_blank">8226939</a>]<br></li>
<li>For some TorR-related proteins such as OmpR or ArcA , it has also been proposed that phosphoryl-ation increases the tendency of the N-terminal ( receiver ) domain to form multimers ( Nakashima et aL , 1991 ; Tardat and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8596446" target="_blank">8596446</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="DOM_collapse_similarity" for="dom_similarity_25">
Requirement of the receiver and phosphotransfer domains of ArcB for efficient dephosphorylation of phosphorylated ArcA in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_25", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>Requirement of the receiver and phosphotransfer domains of ArcB for efﬁcient dephosphorylation of phosphorylated ArcA in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16166540" target="_blank">16166540</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>An in vivo study utilizing ArcB domains borne by a low-copy-number plasmid led to the conclusion that the phosphoryl group from His292 could be transferred to ArcA and that this transfer was regulated by the nature of the carbon source .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10851007" target="_blank">10851007</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we conﬁrmed and extended these studies by analyzing the properties of individual ArcB transmitter and receiver-domains and combinations thereof with the aim of further exploring the pathways for phosphoryl group transfer to ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9286997" target="_blank">9286997</a>]<br></li>
<li>The receiver module with a non-phospho-rylated Asp-576 , however , hinders intermolecular transfer of the phosphoryl group to ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412675" target="_blank">8412675</a>]<br></li>
<li>hen the receiver module is phosphorylated , it allows the transmitter module-P to transfer the phosphoryl group to ArcA , whereas when the receiver module is not phosphorylated , it inhibits this reaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8226939" target="_blank">8226939</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcB then catalyzes autophosphorylation and the transfer of phosphoryl groups to a conserved aspartyl residue of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8588737" target="_blank">8588737</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we constructed plasmids for producing and purifying the two proteins ` ArcB ( an ArcB lacking the two transmembrane portions in the N-terminal region ) and ArcA for the purpose of testing ( i ) whether ArcB undergoes autophosphorylation at both His and Asp residues and ( ii ) whether an Asp residue of ArcA can receive a phosphoryl group from ArcB-P .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1512197" target="_blank">1512197</a>]<br></li>
<li>Depending on aerobic conditions , ArcA is capable of receiving a phosphoryl group from either the catalytic core or the His-containing phosphotransfer ( HPt ) domain of ArcB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10966457" target="_blank">10966457</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the hybrid kinase ArcB , either His-containing domain ( the dimerization domain or the HPt ) can be phosphorylated from ATP and can donate phosphoryl groups to the RR ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10966457" target="_blank">10966457</a>]<br></li>
<li>The conserved His at position 292 in the sensor domain and the three conserved Asp residues at positions 533 , 576 , and 624 ( Fig. 7 ) suggest that the phosphoryl group at His could be transferred intramolecularly to the regulator domain of ArcB itself and/or to one of the three conserved Asp residues of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2201868" target="_blank">2201868</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , ArcA is a typical regulator protein , with only the receiver-domain containing conserved Asp residues at positions 11 and 54 as potential sites for transphosphorylation by phosphorylated ArcB ( ArcB-P ) ( 4 , 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1512197" target="_blank">1512197</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test whether both a His ( presumably at position 292 in the conserved transmitter domain ) and an Asp ( presumably at position 533 or 576 in the conserved receiver-domain ) of ` ArcB are autophosphorylated and whether only an Asp ( presumably at position 11 or 54 in the conserved receiver-domain ) of ArcA is phosphorylated , we took advantage of the known acidic lability and the alkaline stability of the phosphate link to His in contrast to the instability of the phosphate link to Asp under both conditions ( 5 , 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1512197" target="_blank">1512197</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the physiological role of the C-terminal domain is still unknown , the ArcB internal-receiverdomain must be phosphorylated by the kinase domain before transphosphorylation of ArcA can take place ( luchi and Lin , 1992a , b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809780" target="_blank">8809780</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA , on the other hand , is a cytoplasmic response regulator that is activated for transcriptional control by phosphorylation of an aspartyl residue in its receiver module domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since both ArcB and CpxA are expected to communicate with ArcA , it is tempting to suggest that this region plays a particularly important role in the interaction with the cognate regulator domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2201868" target="_blank">2201868</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA is a component of the ArcBA two-component signal transduction system , with the membrane-associated ArcB tripartite sensor kinase comprising a transmitter domain , a receiver-domain and a phosphotransfer domain ( Ishige et al. , 1994 ; Lin & Iuchi , 1991 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcB is the membrane sensor comprising both a transmitter domain and a receiver-domain , and ArcA is the cognate regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8132465" target="_blank">8132465</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this context , it may be significant that ArcB contains a car-boxy-terminal regulator domain resembling ArcA , as well as a typical sensor domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1957353" target="_blank">1957353</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is also possible that the ArcB regulator domain interacts with ArcA so that the phosphorylated product is different from that of CpxA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2201868" target="_blank">2201868</a>]<br></li>
<li>The orientation and protein-protein contacts between the N - and C-terminal domains within an ArcA-P dimer are based on crystallographic data from ArcA and PhoB , respectively ( 15 , 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Tandem direct repeat element recognition by an ArcA dimer is supported by the cocrystal structure of the C-terminal DNA-binding domain of the closely related response regulator PhoB bound to its tandem direct repeat site as a head-to-tail dimer ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The abundance of ArcA binding sites with three DR elements PhoB-response-regulators that consists of the C-terminal DNA-binding domains of the dimer bound to two DRs in a head-to-tail orientation , connected via a ﬂexible linker to the N-terminal regulatory domains that are oriented symmetrically ( head to head ) along a common interface ( 16 , 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The x-ray structures of DrrD and DrrB , OmpR supported by recent structural studies of the dimerized N-terminal domain of ArcA ( 20 ) and PhoB ( 21 ) , suggesting an intriguing insight into the role of phosphorylation and subsequent interaction between OmpR-P molecules through the N-terminal 4 - 5 - 5 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16618701" target="_blank">16618701</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the structure of the activated N-terminal regulatory domain of ArcA bound to a phosphate an-alog is also dimeric but with a symmetric mode of dimerization ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Structural analysis and solution studies of the activated regulatory domain of the response regulator ArcA : a symmetric dimer mediated by the alpha4-beta5-alpha5 face .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regardless of which signal is detected by ArcA and Fnr , the mechanism of signal detection must differ for each protein , given that the proteins do not contain similar or conserved protein domains ( 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
<li>For the ArcA * site , the conserved residues are not indicated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10368146" target="_blank">10368146</a>]<br></li>
<li>This group is subsequently transferred to an aspartate residue in the ArcA protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8226939" target="_blank">8226939</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lanes 1 and 2 contain 800 nM and 400 nM phosphorylated ArcA , respectively ; lane 3 contains 200 nM as-puriﬁed IscR and 800 nM phosphorylated ArcA ; lane 4 contains 200 nM as-puriﬁed IscR ; lane 5 contains no protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , while the VirG and ArcA DNA-binding domains cluster fairly closely to each other in the Fig. 6 tree , the PetR domain has a receiver module that clusters with VirG in Fig. 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7699720" target="_blank">7699720</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , it is possible that in the unphosphorylated state , the amino-terminal receiver-domain of ArcA acts as an inhibitory domain which blocks the carboxy-terminal DNA-binding region from site speciﬁcally interacting with DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , phosphorylation of the receiver-domain of ArcA may result in a conformational change which facilitates oligomerization of the protein and consequent adoption of a site-speciﬁc DNA-binding mode .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>In parallel , similar reactions lacking disodium carbamoyl phosphate were used to prepare His6-ArcA for use in DNA-binding studies .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>Future studies will be directed toward understanding the nature of the phosphorylation-mediated switch in ArcA DNA-binding activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA has features characteristic of a DNA-binding protein ( Drury and Buxton , 1985 ; luchi and Un , 1988 ) but DNA-binding activity of the purified protein has yet to be demonstrated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The mixture was incubated for 90 min at 25 ◦ C , and then the phosphorylated ArcA was used immediately for DNA-binding reaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA-P denotes the phosphorylated ArcA protein which is the DNA-binding species .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20622065" target="_blank">20622065</a>]<br></li>
<li>AcrA-P refers to phosphorylated His6-ArcA protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>The primary structure of ArcA indicates the presence of a helix-turn-helix motif which is believed to be involved in DNA-binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA is a 28-kDa protein that contains a winged-helix-turn-helix motif that interacts with a poorly conserved consensus DNA sequence ( 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA belongs to a typical regulator protein class consisting of a receiver module and a helix-turn-helix motif for recognition of the target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8226939" target="_blank">8226939</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="DOM_collapse_similarity" for="dom_similarity_67">
( Bottom ) ArcA consists of an N-terminal receiver-domain ( D2 ) containing the conserved Asp54 and a C-terminal helix-turn-helix ( HTH ) domain ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10851007" target="_blank">10851007</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_67", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>( Bottom ) ArcA is shown with its N-terminal receiver-domain containing the conserved Asp54 and its C-terminal helix-turn-helix ( HTH ) domain ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9286997" target="_blank">9286997</a>]<br></li></div>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">ArcA evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>Acknowledgements We are extremely grateful to Prof. F. Lottspeich ( Martinsried , Germany ) for confirming the identity of ArcA by amino acid sequencing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Greater similarity ( Fig. 3 ) was found with ArcA ( 43 % identity ) , OmpR ( 32 % identity ) , and PhoB ( 29 % identity ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8083154" target="_blank">8083154</a>]<br></li>
<li>Its strong similarity ( 43 % identity ) with ArcA , the general aerobic regulator ( 14 ) , first suggested that TorR could mediate the anaerobic regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8083154" target="_blank">8083154</a>]<br></li>
<li>The latter belongs to both subject to dual control by both a growing family of CRP-related regulators ArcA and FNR8 ,2 ~ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1957353" target="_blank">1957353</a>]<br></li>
<li>sodA belongs to the ArcA moduton ( Tardat and Touati , 1991 ) and is also negatively regulated by Fnr ( Hassan and Sun , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the basis of additional homology within the carboxy-terminal domain , TorR has been recognized as a member of the OmpR subfamily of response regulators , which includes numerous members in E. coil ( such as ArcA , OmpR , or PhoB ) but also in many other bacterial species ( Aiba et aL , 1993 ; Mills et aL , 1993 ; Nagasawa et aL , 1993 ; Parkinson and Kofoid , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8596446" target="_blank">8596446</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other regulators , including other LysR family members , the E. coil anaerobic regulator ArcA , and the Xenopus transcription factor TFIIIA , also protect long sequences from DNAase I digestion ( Tardat and Touati , 1993 ; Engelke et al. , 1980 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8087856" target="_blank">8087856</a>]<br></li>
<li>In E. coli , members of these homologous families have been identified in more than 10 different adaptive response systems ( for a review , see reference 38 ) , including chemotaxis ( CheA-CheY ) , nitrogen regulation ( NtrB-NtrC ) , phosphate regulation ( PhoR-PhoB ) , nitrate reductase regulation ( NarX-NarL ) , oxygen regulation ( ArcB-ArcA ) , and osmotic porin regulation ( EnvZ-OmpR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8282700" target="_blank">8282700</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the ﬁnding that the bet regulon belongs to the ArcA modulon is in accordance with a well-known pattern which has been pointed out previously , namely , that this two-component regulatory system often controls E. coli functions which have their counterparts in the mammalian mitochondria ( 23 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA-binding studies Purification of the His6-CpxR protein from IPTG-induced E. coli ECL3000 cells transformed with pREP4 and pQE30CpxR was performed as described previously for a similarly tagged protein ( His6-ArcA ) of the two-component response regulator family ( Lynch and Lin 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9159398" target="_blank">9159398</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA and ArcB belong to a family of homologous two-component regulatory systems in eubacteria .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1512197" target="_blank">1512197</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcB protein is a transmembrane protein which senses unfavourable respiratory conditions , undergoes autophosphorylation , then transfers its phosphoryl group to the ArcA regulatory protein , which then becomes functionally active ( luchi and Lin , 1992 ; luchi et al. , 1990 ) , Analogies with the OmpR-EnvZ family of two-component regulatory systems ( Stock et al. , 1989 ) , genetic evidence and the finding of a helix-turn-helix motif in the ArcA protein suggest that ArcA binds to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>CpxR shares homology with other two-component DNA-binding proteins , including OmpR and ArcA ( Dong et al. 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7883164" target="_blank">7883164</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other represented functions in our dataset relate to sensing and stimulus responses , mostly proteins belonging to two component systems , such as ArcA , RcsB , CpxR and EvgA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25518064" target="_blank">25518064</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA belongs to a typical regulator protein class consisting of a receiver module and a helix-turn-helix motif for recognition of the target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8226939" target="_blank">8226939</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both ArcA and ArcB show similarity to members of the sensor-regulator class of proteins ( 25 ) , and it has been proposed that ArcB is a histidine kinase that phosphor-ylates , and thereby activates , ArcA in response to anoxia ( 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>The anaerobic induction is dependent on two transcriptional activators ( 2 , 8 ) : ( i ) the ArcA response regulator ( 18 ) , which is activated by the ArcB sensor in response to reduced respiration ( 17 , 19 ) , and ( ii ) the AppY protein , which is a member of the AraC family of transcriptional activators ( 3 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9079897" target="_blank">9079897</a>]<br></li>
<li>Synthesis of the AppY protein is regulated by the ArcA regulator , which responds to changes in respiration ( 21 ) , and the AppY protein is itself activated in response to anaerobiosis ( 7 ) , probably by association with a low-molecular-weight effector like some of the other members of the AraC family of activators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8655536" target="_blank">8655536</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
