<li>TorC autoregulation is different from tor anaerobic control The torCAD operon is fully induced in anaerobiosis but , in contrast to all other known anaerobic respiratory systems , this control is mediated neither by FNR , a pleiotropic anae-robic regulator , nor by ArcA , a response regulator involved in redox control of numerous genes ( Simon et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10411745" target="_blank">10411745</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genes and regulators responding to O2 and other acceptors FNR and ArcA , as shown earlier for NarL and NarP , control different sets of target genes Žreviewed in w4 ,5,9,11,12,44 x. FNR acts as the major regulator of anaerobic metabolism and ArcA as the regulator of aerobic metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9230919" target="_blank">9230919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Remarkably , anaerobic control is mediated neither by FNR , the general anaerobic regulator , nor by ArcA , another anaerobic global regulator ( luchi and Lin , 1988 ; Pascal et aL , 1984 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8596446" target="_blank">8596446</a>]<br></li>
<li>Adaptation to anaerobic growth is regulated by two global transcription factors , FNR ( fumarate and nitrate reductase regulator ) and ArcA ( anaerobic respiratory control ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16417494" target="_blank">16417494</a>]<br></li>
