<li>Under anaerobic conditions ArcA mostly negatively regulates genes involved in the TCA-cycle and electron transport [ 26-28 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19715602" target="_blank">19715602</a>]<br></li>
<li>The secondary promoter Plpd is under the control of ArcA , which is the global repressor of TCA-cycle genes under anaerobic conditions ( 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513468" target="_blank">17513468</a>]<br></li>
<li>This finding has led to the proposal that ArcA is a transcriptional repressor of genes encoding enzymes of aerobic metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>Phosphorylated ArcA ( ArcA-P ) generally behaves as an anaerobic repressor , negatively controlling aerobic-respiration although some genes are activated by ArcA-P [ 15 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8824175" target="_blank">8824175</a>]<br></li>
<li>The principle function of ArcA appears to be as an anaerobic repressor of genes encoding enzymes functional in aerobic metabolism ( 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>Phosphorylated ArcA directly regulates many genes , including those encoding aerobic or anaerobic respiratory enzymes , and typically functions as a repressor ( 19 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>During anaerobic growth , the regulator ArcA represses expression of enzymes involved in aerobic metabolism ( 27 ) and activates expression of pyruvate formate-lyase , hydrogenase 1 , and cytochrome d oxidase ( 9 , 25 , 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>During anaerobic growth , ArcA represses transcription of several genes involved in aerobic metabolism , including the cyo operon ( 23 ) , and activates transcription of the pfl gene ( 35 ) and the cyd operon ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071219" target="_blank">8071219</a>]<br></li>
<li>During anaerobic growth , ArcA represses transcription of several genes involved in aerobic metabolism ( 17 ) and activates transcription of the pyruvate formate-lyase ( pfl ) gene ( 30 ) as well as the cytochrome d oxidase ( cydAB ) operon ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071220" target="_blank">8071220</a>]<br></li>
<li>When activated anaerobically by the membrane sensor protein ArcB , ArcA typically represses a number of genes involved in aerobic metabolism [ 18 ] and activates genes necessary for anaerobic growth [ 9,22 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18683632" target="_blank">18683632</a>]<br></li>
<li>FNR and ArcA are involved in sensing the redox status of the cell to regulate genes involved in respiration under aerobic and anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12582243" target="_blank">12582243</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA is the major regulator of aerobic metabolism and represses the genes of aerobic metabolism under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9230919" target="_blank">9230919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under anaerobic conditions , ArcA , the response regulator of the two-component ArcA-ArcB system , represses many genes for aerobic functions and activates transcription of some other genes ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12923108" target="_blank">12923108</a>]<br></li>
<li>The unorthodox histidin kinase ArcB together with the response regulator ArcA regulates the expression of many genes which are involved in the adaptation of the bacteria during the switch between aerobic and anaerobic growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12135487" target="_blank">12135487</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dependence on the ArcA ( aerobic-respiration control regulator ) and Fnr transcription factors for anaerobic inductionwas tested for several focA-lacZ and pfl-lacZ gene fusions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>The P6 promoter has a poorly conserved Abbreviations : ArcA , aerobic-respiration control regulator ; Fnr , - 10 hexamer sequence and lacks a -35 hexamer se-fumarate-nitratereduction regulator ; PfI , pyruvate formate-lyase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>In spite of such high similarity , Fnr is associated not with the transport system but with the switching of respiration styles ; i.e. under the anaerobic condition , Fnr activates the transcription of anaerobic enzyme genes , repressing the transcription of oxidase gene ( Spiro & Guest , 1991 ) , together with ArcA , one of the response regulators in Group 1 , that represses the transcription of aerobic-respiration enzyme genes ( Iuchi et al. , 1990 ; Iuchi & Lin , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8729576" target="_blank">8729576</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two regulatory systems -- Fnr and ArcA -- were investigated to explore the regulatory role of Crp over fumA and fumC because fumarase genes are involved in the aerobic TCA-cycle and anaerobic respiratory pathways .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 3A shows that whereas the gIpACB operon ( encoding the dehydrogenase for anaerobic-respiration ) is a member of the Fnr modulon , the gIpD operon ( encoding the dehydrogenase for aerobic-respiration ) is a member of the ArcA modulon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412675" target="_blank">8412675</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to its function as a transcriptional activator , ArcA modulates the activities of the aerobic repressor ( H-NS ) and the anaerobic repressor ( Fnr ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two giobal transcription regulators , Fnr and ArcA , play a major role in the adaptation of tiie cell to anaerobic and aerobic environments .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>The newly identified transmitter module and anaerobic regulation by ArcB As mentioned above , ArcB controls the anaerobic repression of several operons by phosphorylating its cognate response regulator , ArcA ( Drury and Buxton , 1985 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7957084" target="_blank">7957084</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcB sensor controls the anaerobic repression of several aerobic respiratory operons by modulating its partner regulator , ArcA ( luchi and Lin , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809780" target="_blank">8809780</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcB functions to activate ArcA during anaerobic conditions via protein-phosphorylation reactions ( 7 , 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
<li>Most of the anaerobic induction in the wild type is mediated by the ArcA response regulator ( 9 ) , which is activated via phosphorylation by the ArcB sensor under conditions of reduced respiration ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8655536" target="_blank">8655536</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has recently been shown that , under anaerobic growth conditions , Fpg activity increases in strains deﬁcient in the global regulators Fur , FNR , and ArcA ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10400579" target="_blank">10400579</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutagenesis analysis of ArcA indicated that ROS resistance was mediated through a distinct signaling-pathway from that used in anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19715602" target="_blank">19715602</a>]<br></li>
<li>We therefore investigated the role that ArcA may play in the negative regulation of fadJ , fadI and fadK under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>Induction was dependent on the transcriptional regulator ArcA , with a second transcriptional regulator , FNR , playing a negative role speciﬁcally under anaerobic conditions ( S. Darie and R. P. Gunsalus , J. Bacteriol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8550494" target="_blank">8550494</a>]<br></li>
<li>A balanced aerobic growth on glycerol depends on three global regulators : cAMP-CRP as the principal inducer of the glycerol catabolic regulon ( including glpF , glpK and glpD ) ; Cra ( FruR ) as regulator of some gluconeogenic genes , and ArcA as regulator of several central metabolic genes including the TCA-cycle and others involved in respiration [ 1,5 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22513097" target="_blank">22513097</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA is a regulator of re-spiratory genes encoding cytochromes o and d oxidases , as well as fermentative genes encoding pyruvate and L-lactate dehydrogenases ( for a review , see reference 23 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8955321" target="_blank">8955321</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
