<li>In a preliminary search for speciﬁc DNA binding sites for His6-ArcA and His6-ArcA-P in the glt-sdh intergenic region by EMS assays , a 769-bp DNA fragment ( derived from pBTKSgltA-sdh1 ) , which includes all o the three known promoters and overlaps the ORF 's of both gltA and sdhC ( 9 , 40 , 50 , 51 ) , was used .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>In a preliminary search for speciﬁc DNA binding sites for His6-ArcA and His6-ArcA-P in the lct operon , EMS assays were performed with restriction fragments spanning a 6,633-bp region which includes the complete coding sequences of the lctPRD genes and 1,698 bp upstream of the initiation codon of LctP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>EMS assays were initially used to locate speciﬁc DNA binding sites for His6-ArcA and His6-ArcA-P in the cydAB promoter region , using DNA fragments ( derived from pBTKScyd1 ) which span a 1,017-bp region including 974 bp upstream of the initiation codon of CydA and therein the previously characterized cydAB promoter ( 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>To understand the contribution of each DR in ArcA repression of icdA , they were mutated toward or away from 5 = - TGTTA-3 = ( Fig. 1C ) , the most conserved sequence within each ArcA DR element ( hereinafter referred to as the consensus ) and , based on the PhoB DNA cocrystal structure ( 15 ) , the region likely contacted by ArcA in the major groove .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , because ArcA DNA elements are direct repeats , they can be found either in the same or in the opposite orientation from the promoter elements , providing additional ﬂexibility for coding repressor information within a constrained sequence space .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The extent of the DNA sequence at site A-3 protected by ArcA , which was approximately 94 bp at low ArcA concentration extending up lo 141 bp when the ArcA concen-ttation was increased , proved very surprising .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>This sequence matched 6 of the 10 bases of the consensus ArcA sequence ( 5 ′ [ A/T ] GTTAATTA [ A/T ] ) [ 12 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15808934" target="_blank">15808934</a>]<br></li>
<li>The inverted bracket represents the putative ArcA consensus sequence suggested ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA sequence determinants for ArcA binding have been obscured by the long , degenerate DNA elements bound by ArcA in vitro ( 5 -- 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Comparison of the DNA sequence within the bound region to the predicted ArcA consensus ( 5 = - GTTAATTAAATGTT A-3 =) ( 10 , 24 ) shows a match from position 17 to 1 on the bottom strand ( Fig. 2C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two previous reports suggested primary DNA sequence motifs which may represent an ArcA box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8892825" target="_blank">8892825</a>]<br></li>
<li>but we have no indication of a DNA motif specifically recognized by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8412671" target="_blank">8412671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since no consensus sequence is available for ArcA it is currently not possible to differentiate between its involvement in a direct protein-DNA interaction at this promoter and an indirect protein-protein interaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA is a 28-kDa protein that contains a winged helix-turn-helix motif that interacts with a poorly conserved consensus DNA sequence ( 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA protections extended from about positions 215 to 127 relative to the start site of icd transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA protein , when prephosphorylated with acetyl phosphate ( Materials and Methods ) , protected a 42-bp region of DNA from positions 215 to 127 bp relative to the start site of icd transcription ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA was shown to bind directly within the icd regulatory region , where DNase I footprinting studies revealed a 42-bp ArcA-phosphate-protected region overlapping the start site of icd transcription ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>The consensus for ArcA recognition , TGTTAATTAA , as determined by Lynch & Lin ( 1996 ) , was indeed found between positions -13 and -4 of the aldA promoter with a conservation of 10/10 nucleotides .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9202484" target="_blank">9202484</a>]<br></li>
<li>Attention has previously been drawn to this ArcA site by Lynch & Lin ( 1996 ) even though there are a further 10 potential ArcA sites matching the consensus at 3 7 out of 10 positions , in the untranscribed intergenic region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9421904" target="_blank">9421904</a>]<br></li>
<li>This inconsistency is likely due to the inaccuracy of the bioinformatic search which utilized a sequence motif of `` ( 5 ′ [ A/T ] GTTAATTA [ A/T ] 3 ′ ) '' as the template and the motif was proposed as the ArcA binding site by Lynch and Lin ( 1996 ) following the DNA foot-printing analysis of a limited number of ArcA regulated promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Examination of the hya regulatory region failed to reveal any recognition sequence for ArcA similar to that proposed by Drapal & Sawers ( 1995 ) , but it did identify a sequence similar to that proposed by Lynch & Lin ( 1996b ) to be required for ArcA binding ( Fig. 2b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10537212" target="_blank">10537212</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the mechanism of repression has not been well studied , ArcA binding sites within the promoters of repressed operons contain a variable number of direct repeat ( DR ) sequence elements while almost exclusively overlapping the 70 RNA polymerase ( 70-RNAP ) DNA recognition elements ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like ArcA , Fur binding sites are variable in length ( 30 to 103 bp ) and contain multiple Fur recognition elements of differing predicted strengths and locations with respect to the promoter elements ( 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Tandem direct repeat element recognition by an ArcA dimer is supported by the cocrystal structure of the C-terminal DNA binding domain of the closely related response regulator PhoB bound to its tandem direct repeat site as a head-to-tail dimer ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>four turns of B-DNA ) than would be expected from binding of a 28-kDa ArcA monomeric protein as puriﬁed for use in these experiments , which suggests that multiple ArcA mole-cules are bound at the icd regulatory site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additional DNA determinants must exist for ArcA recognition and binding to the icd DNA site of 42 bp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>A 10-bp ArcA DR element , PWM , derived from the conservation of bases within aligned DR1 and DR2 elements from 128 sequences bound by ArcA in vivo ( 4 ) was used to guide the design of binding site mutations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previous analyses of these footprinted regions have proposed a 15-bp DNA site ( 5 = - GTTAATTAAATGTTA-3 =) consisting of two adjacent direct repeats ( underlined ) as the minimal ArcA recognition site ( 11 -- 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , recent analysis of the chromosomal binding regions of ArcA identiﬁed by chromatin immunoprecipitation-DNA sequencing ( ChIP-seq ) suggested that the minimal ArcA binding site is composed of two 10-bp direct repeat elements ( 5 = - ATGTTAAAAA-1-ATGTTAAAAA-3 = ) ( 4 ) raises the question of how ArcA dimers bind to a DNA site with an odd number of DR elements .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data have led to a model for ArcA and other OmpR / FIG 1 ( A ) Sequence logo for the minimal ArcA binding site consisting of two 10-bp direct repeat elements ( 5 = - ATGTTAAAAA-1-ATGTTAAAAA-3 =) ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>IHF binds to a single site in the pfl regulatory region midway between promoters 6 and 7 and it is difficult to account for the dependence on this protein without invoking long-range protein-protein interaction between ArcA bound at promoter 7 and a distinct component of the transcriptional machinery bound at promoter 6 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>]<br></li>
<li>A further possibility is that ArcA binds to fhe DNA as an oligotner , Tardat and Touati ( 1993 ) also identified a tather large ( 65 bp ) ArcA-bind/ng site in the sodA promoter and they suggested that ArcA may be oligomeric .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although no specific ArcA-binding site has been found to date , the sodA regulatory region protected by ArcA is devoid of palindromic structure and is A/T rich ( Tardat and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8596446" target="_blank">8596446</a>]<br></li>
<li>These resuKs demonstrate that operator sequences for the ArcA protein are present within the 500 bp of the pro-inoter-regulatory region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The isolated protein binds specificatly to DNA fragments frofn the pf / promoter-regulatory region and we could characterize four distinct sites recognized by ArcA , Furthermore , binding activity could be enhanced substantially by incubation of the protein with iow-molecular-weight pbospho-donors , such as acetyl or carbamoyi phospbate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcript and sequence analyses reveai that the arcA upstream regulatory region lies within a 530 bp non-coding DNA fragment , which contains five putative promoter sequences and a putative Fnr-binding site , identification of the transcription start sites indicates that transcription occurs in aerobiosis from three constitutive upstream promoters ( Pe , Pd , Pc ) - In anaerobiosis an additionai compieteiy Fnr-dependent transcript starting at P̂ , is present ; expression from Pa is reduced in the absence of ArcA , and Fnr activation at P̂ biocks the weak anaerobic-dependent expression from Pb - Fnr activation of arcA transcription may piay an important role in the co-ordination of expression of genes associated with aerobic and anaerobic metabolism during environmentai changes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine whether adding a fourth DR element facilitates ArcA-P binding and increases the footprint length , a consensus DR element ( 5 = - TGTTA-3 =) was added at the same spacing ( 11 bp CTC ) to either the 3 = or the 5 = end of the three-DR ArcA binding site within the icdA promoter region and DNase I footprinting experiments were performed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>The identity of the DNA site ( s ) that ArcA phosphate recognizes and binds to at the mdh promoter region is not yet known .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592446" target="_blank">7592446</a>]<br></li>
<li>The main binding site ( s ) for ArcA appeared to be at the betT side of the promoter region , either within a 51-bp region which is adjacent to the 89-bp promoter region or , more likely , at the DraI site separating these regions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>The location of the ArcA binding site within the hya promoter region was determined by DNase I footprinting , which showed that phosphorylated ArcA bound hyaA DNA from position 32 to 3 relative to the transcription start site ( Fig. 2A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA-binding activity of purified ArcA was stable to shifts in pH. Identification of muitipie ArcA-binding sites in the pfl promoter-regulatory region To localize the ArcA-binding sites in the pfl promoterregulatory region more precisely , the labelled DNA fragment was restricted with various enzymes that have a single recognition sequence within the regulatory DNA sequence prior to its inclusion in the gel retardation assay .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>Examination of the DNA sequence for the suggested ArcA consensus sequence ( A/TGTTAATTAA/T ) and consensus Fnr binding site ( TTGAT-N4-ATCAA ) ( 14 , 18 , 19 ) failed to reveal perfectly matched consensus sequences for ArcA and Fnr regulatory proteins within the tpx promoter region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is feasible that there may be severai ArcA recognition sequences located within this region of DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is not yet known what DNA sequences are recognized by ArcA for binding to DNA and where it binds within the hemA regulatory region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , two overlapping putative -RCB- ArcA sites ( 7 10 bases matching the consensus centred at ® 97 , AGTTgATgtA , and ® 94 , TGTaAAacAA ; non-consensus bases in lower case ) were detected within ® ± the far upstream ( 93 5 ) FNR site that is responsible for the anaerobic downregulation of yﬁD expression ( Green et al. , 1998 ) , suggesting that ArcA might prevent FNR binding at this location and thereby increase yﬁD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11932447" target="_blank">11932447</a>]<br></li>
<li>The putative binding sites for cAMP-CRP and the experimentally verified binding sites for ArcA within PsdhC are absent from E. coli MG1655ΔPsdh : : Ptet .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17273855" target="_blank">17273855</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , it is not possible to locate potential ArcA-binding sites by sequence analysis , although it is presumed that dctA is directly repressed by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10482502" target="_blank">10482502</a>]<br></li>
<li>IscR and downstream ArcA sites are boxed in the E. coli sequence ( top ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequences showing similarity with the consensus ArcA box within the ArcA-P-mediated DNase I protection regions of the ptsG promoter were found ( Fig. 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15252051" target="_blank">15252051</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcA-P consensus sequences are shown in bold characters ( in regions I and II ) , and the mutated base pairs are denoted by ® lled circle Fig. 2 Electrophoretic mobility shift analysis of ArcA and ArcA-P binding to wild-type aldA promoter DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10071223" target="_blank">10071223</a>]<br></li>
<li>For either ArcA consensus sequence , additional regions of ArcA-phosphate-protected DNA which extend by 2.5 to 3 additional turns of B-DNA are seen 59 and 39 of these sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>The H-NS protected sequences overlap the Fnr and ArcA binding sites and the P1 , P2 , P3 and P4 promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is unclear whether the ArcA-binding sequences in the DcuR-protected regions are a consequence of similarities between the consensus binding sequences for ArcA and DcuR or whether there could be competition between ArcA and DcuR at these sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996819" target="_blank">14996819</a>]<br></li>
<li>Putative Fnr-binding sites are shown , and the regions of DNA protected by ArcA from DNase I cleavage ( 5 ) are depicted as hatched boxes , while the location of the integration host factor-binding site ( 15 ) is shown as a black box above the sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>The size of DNA fragments around the consensus sites which is protected upon binding of ArcA or NarL from DNase I digestion suggests that both proteins are bound as oligomers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9230919" target="_blank">9230919</a>]<br></li>
<li>A site similar to the ArcA consensus sequence has been identified upstream of the 3 cyoA promoter and was also shown to be subject to regulation by FNR in our previous study ( 1 ) , but this is likely indirect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Prior workers had predicted the transcriptional start site to lie 17 bp downstream of the ArcA binding site ( 8 ) , but since this would have the mRNA initiate within the known fadH coding sequence ( 21 ) , the prediction was clearly incorrect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20622065" target="_blank">20622065</a>]<br></li>
<li>Analyses of the E. coli sequence showed three different conserved sites upstream of the predicted transcriptional start site , which would be binding sites for the FadR repressor , the ArcA repressor , and the CRP activator ( Fig. 2D ) , the ﬁrst two of which had been predicted by others .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20622065" target="_blank">20622065</a>]<br></li>
<li>The − 35 and − 10 regions and the proposed ArcA binding site are boxed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15808934" target="_blank">15808934</a>]<br></li>
<li>communication ) that deviates from the previously proposed ArcA binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although ArcA binding-site consensus sequences have been proposed ( 8 , 33 ) , they do not allow the accurate prediction of ArcA-binding sites ( 47 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10482502" target="_blank">10482502</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although ArcA consensus binding sites have been proposed from footprinting studies with several ArcA-controlled promoters [ 1,7,17,26 ] , a region resembling an ArcA-binding site within the nrdDG promoter region could not be identified .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18683632" target="_blank">18683632</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of a single ArcA site at the lpd promoter contrasts markedly with the presence of four ArcA binding sites associated with the sdh promoter [ 17 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>One binding site for IHF ( Sirko et aL , 1993 ) and four binding sites for ArcA have been identified ( Drapal and Sawers , 1995 ) in the promoter-regulatory region of the operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8709852" target="_blank">8709852</a>]<br></li>
<li>A putative ArcA binding site overlapping the 35 element is indicated and residues close to the ArcA box consensus , as deﬁned by McGuire et al ( 1999 ) , are shown with stars .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both sites contain core regions highly similar to the ArcA consensus binding site ( McGuire et al. 1999 ; Liu and de Wulf 2004 ; Salmon et al. 2005 ) ( shown below the sequence of the promoter region in Fig. 3C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>The regions of ArcA protection are overlined ( coding stand ) or underlined ( non-coding strand ) and an ArcA binding-site consensus [ 11 ] is shown above the sequence ; W = T/A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , the protected region contains a sequence that matches the ArcA binding-site consensus , WGTTAATTAW [ 11 ] , at 8 out of 10 positions ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the betI strand , this DraI site is part of a TATTTAA sequence ( Fig. 2B ) , which recently has been suggested as the consensus for ArcA binding ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , the transcription start point of the lpd promoter was defined by primer extension analysis , and an ArcA binding site , TGTTAACAAT , overlapping the lpd promoter and matching the consensus at 8 out of 10 positions , was identified by in vitro footprint analysis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9868788" target="_blank">9868788</a>]<br></li>
<li>A putative ArcA binding site ( TGTTCAAATC ) was found 79 base pairs upstream of the hcaR transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15808934" target="_blank">15808934</a>]<br></li>
<li>The putative FadR binding site ( AACTCATCCGACC/TACAT ) overlaps the transcriptional start site and the downstream ArcA binding site ( TAACAAT/ATATTTTA ) ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20622065" target="_blank">20622065</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcriptional start points indicated by the primer extension analysis , the most probable 235 and 210 boxes , the deduced translational start codons of BetI and BetT , and a putative ArcA binding site are boxed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>In a few cases , adjacent LexA sites are bound in a cooperative manner , further enhancing the sensitivity to changes in signal ( 36 ) , as hypothesized for the ArcA binding sites located upstream of acs and astC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161193" target="_blank">25161193</a>]<br></li>
<li>As predicted from the role of activator , only the phosphorylated form of ArcA binds to the moe upstream sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11357510" target="_blank">11357510</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is conceivable that an ArcA oligomer ( which is known to form upon phosphorylation [ Jeon et al. 2001 ] ) binds to both sites and thereby may induce the formation of a DNA loop that includes the rpoSp1 promoter sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here we demonstrate that the phosphorylated response regulator ArcA is a direct repressor of rpoS transcription that binds to two sites flanking the major rpoS promoter , with the upstream site overlapping an activating cAMP-CRP-binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , these data demonstrate that phosphorylated ArcA directly binds to two specific sites located upstream and immediately downstream of the rpoSp1 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA directly binds to two sites in the rpoSp1 promoter region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
