<li>This was accomplished by the use of DNA microarrays to analyze gene expression profiles in E. coli cells cultured at steady-state growth rates under aerobic ( O2 ) or anaerobic ( O2 ) growth 84 This paper is available on line at http://www.jbc.org conditions and in cells cultured under anaerobic growth conditions in the presence ( O , ArcA ) or absence ( O , ArcA ) of 2 2 the ArcA protein or in otherwise arcA and arcA isogenic strains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The experimental cell growth conditions were as follows : wild-type E. coli K12 strain ( ArcA ) cultured under aerobic conditions ( O2 Arc ) , wild-type E. coli K12 strain ( ArcA ) cultured under anaerobic conditions ( O2 Arc ) , and isogenic E. coli K12 strain lacking the arcA gene cultured under anaerobic conditions ( O2 Arc ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>These experiments show that about one-half of the genes whose expression levels are affected by aerobic to anaerobic transitions are also affected by the ArcA protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results of the gene expression profiling experiments further show that as many as two-thirds of the genes whose expression levels are affected by the ArcA protein are also affected by the FNR protein ( 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fact that aerobic expression is also reduced in the arcA mutant ( Table 1 ) indicates that ArcA is also involved in aerobic expression of pﬂ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fact that the control of this promoter was independent of ArcA and Fnr ( Table 4 ) suggests that the prior observation by Iuchi et al. ( 9 ) that an arcA mutant was elevated for a-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase activity when grown under anaerobic conditions is accounted for by the regulated expression of the sucAB genes from the upstream sdhC promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209026" target="_blank">9209026</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression Pattern IV : Increased Expression during Anaerobiosis and No Change in an ArcA Strain -- The six genes of this cluster ( Table IV ) showed elevated expression under anaerobic growth conditions , but were not affected by deletion of the arcA allele .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Deletion of the arcA gene caused about a 2-fold increase in the ptsG expression , and overexpression of ArcA significantly decreased glucose consumption .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15252051" target="_blank">15252051</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , uvrA gene expression was repressed when ArcA was induced in E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16140472" target="_blank">16140472</a>]<br></li>
<li>Only one gene in this expression pattern , glcC , was also identified in the study by Liu and De Wulf ( 22 ) ; however , their results indicated that glcG is repressed by ArcA ( 2.6-fold ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the aerobic/anaerobic control of fumA and fumC gene expression involves ArcA repression at both the fumA and fumC promoters , while Fnr regulates fumC at a distance from the fumA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>This control is complex : it involves action by ArcA and Fnr as negative regulators of fumA and fumC expression from the fumA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similar results were recently reported for the role of ArcA in gltA gene expression ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592446" target="_blank">7592446</a>]<br></li>
<li>These findings suggest that ArcA acts as a negative regulator of aldA gene expression under anaerobiosis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9202484" target="_blank">9202484</a>]<br></li>
<li>These ﬁndings demonstrate that ArcA is a negative regulator of fumA and fumC gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>The remaining gene , frdB , is a member of pattern VII ( decreased expression during anaerobiosis and decreased expression in a ArcA strain ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15699038" target="_blank">15699038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Compan and D. Touati The molecular mechanism of ArcA control of gene expression is largely uncharacterized .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcA control of fumC gene expression is also complex : it requires the combined interactions of ArcA at both the fumA and fumC promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592392" target="_blank">7592392</a>]<br></li>
<li>By contrast , the recently observed Fnr-dependent control of arcA gene expression has subjected models for Fnr and ArcA control of gene expression to reevaluation ( 3 , 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7601854" target="_blank">7601854</a>]<br></li>
<li>The model proposed for ArcA and Fnr control of cydAB expression may be proposed for hemA gene expression ( 6 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>The roles of ArcA and Fnr as principal regulators of tpx gene expression in response to oxygen are discussed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , for maximum aerobic expression of the sodA gene both ArcA and Fnr must be present , while Fur must be absent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1565612" target="_blank">1565612</a>]<br></li>
<li>A mechanism for Fnr control of icd gene expression is less clear than for the ArcA protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , ArcA and Fnr function as negative regulators of icd gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fnr and ArcA serve as transcription regulators of fumarase gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>As another transcription regulator that controls fatty acid metabolism , ArcA has been shown to strongly ( > 20-fold ) repress the expression of 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase encoded by the fadB gene , and to weakly repress acyl-CoA dehydrogenase encoded by the fadE gene , under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>Apart from its positive role in sex factor functions ( 12 , 14 ) , this is only the second example of ArcA functioning as a transcriptional activator of aerobic or anaerobic gene expression in E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcA protein of E. coli is a global transcription factor that mediates gene expression in response to changing redox conditions ( Lynch & Lin , 1996b ; Iuchi & Lin , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fumA gene transcription is positively regulated by Crp and repressed by ArcA and its expression is predominant under aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22513097" target="_blank">22513097</a>]<br></li>
<li>The second transcription factor involved in oontrolling anaerobic gene expression is the ArcA protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The second protein that regulates anaerobic gene expression is ArcA , which was identified as being necessary for repressing expression of the succinate dehydrogenase gene under anaerobic conditions ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA , when activated , can then bind to regulatory DNA sites to mediate both positive and negative control of gene expression ( 8 , 9 ) : cyo-ABCDE expression is repressed under anaerobic conditions , while cydAB expression is activated ( 3 , 4 , 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576043" target="_blank">8576043</a>]<br></li>
<li>FnrS is involved in gene regulation after the shift from aerobic to anaerobic conditions , and its expression is activated by the transcription factors FNR and ArcA ( 20 , 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23980183" target="_blank">23980183</a>]<br></li>
<li>During an-aerobic cell growth conditions , this repression is optimal : under some conditions of aerobic cell growth , ArcA appears to still partially repress gene expression ( ca .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>This anaerobic response is modulated by the ArcA protein , which functions as a repressor of mdh gene expression under both aerobic and anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7592446" target="_blank">7592446</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , these results show that gene expression changes are consistent with ArcA being active in ECOM4LA under aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>Global gene expression suggests that ArcA is active in ECOM4LA in aerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results of immunoblotting experiments also demonstrated that ArcA and Fnr regulatory proteins repressed thiol peroxidase gene expression during anaerobic growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , the results presented here indicate that ArcA and Fnr regulatory proteins play a role in repression of the E. coli tpx gene under anaerobic growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>The differences observed in tpx gene expression during aerobic vs. anaerobic growth conditions were also reported for several tricarboxylic acid cycle genes , including sdhC , gltA , mdh , and for some respiratory pathway genes , frdABCD , dmsABC , narGHJI although the molecular basis for this ArcA - and Fnr-independent control is not understood ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary The ArcA and Fnr regulators of Escherichia coii , both of which are activated in anaerobic conditions , negatively regulate the sodA gene ( coding for manganese superoxide dismutase ) , but Fnr has no effect on anaerobic sodA expression in a \ arcAAfnr background ( Compan and Touati , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>The anaerobic control of icd expression by ArcA and that by Fnr appear to occur relatively independently of each other .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArcA and Fnr proteins provide anaerobic control of sucA expression at a distance as revealed by analysis of the larger sdhCDAB-sucA-lacZ fusion ( Fig. 2 , Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209026" target="_blank">9209026</a>]<br></li>
<li>The aerobic and anaerobic control of gltA4-lacZ expression is due primarily to the arcA gene product ( Table 4 ; Fig. 5 ) , whereas sdhCDAB gene expression is controlled by both ArcA and Fnr ( 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to the aerobic increase in FumA and FumC activities , FumB is more abundant under anaerobic conditions and fumB gene expression requires ArcA and Fnr as transcriptional activators ( Tseng , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fnr represses sdhCDAB expression but oniy during anaerobic conditions , Wby does tbe aerobic/anaerobic control of sdhCDAB gene expression require two regulators , ArcA and Fnr ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dual control of tpx gene expression regulated by ArcA and Fnr proteins appears to provide maximum protection against the toxicity of oxidative stress during aerobic and anaerobic growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10794600" target="_blank">10794600</a>]<br></li>
<li>The extent of ArcA control of gitA and sdhCDAB gene expression under aerobic conditions is in marked contrast to the lack of Fnr control under the same conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051021" target="_blank">8051021</a>]<br></li>
<li>The aerobic/anaerobic control of sdhCDAB gene expression is provided by the two cellular regulatory proteins , ArcA and Fnr -LCB- Table 3 , Fig , 3 ) , ArcA functions as a repressor of sc / / 7CD / \ S-operon expression under both aerobic and anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7783618" target="_blank">7783618</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , aerobic expression of the focA gene was reduced by the p6A mutation , as was the dependence on ArcA for anaerobic induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>Aerobic expression was also reduced partially by Fnr and ArcA control anaerobic induction of focA the p6-2 mutation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9084161" target="_blank">9084161</a>]<br></li>
<li>whose expression is reduced by ArcA during anaerobic growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565118" target="_blank">7565118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results clearly demonstrate that ArcA represses expression of arcZ during anaerobic growth , the expected condition for ArcA to be active .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>Possibly , the differences in anaerobic expression of the hya operon in glucose medium and glycerol medium reflect differences in the levels of expression of the appY gene and/or in the levels of phosphorylation of the ArcA protein during anaerobic growth in these two media .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071220" target="_blank">8071220</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA protein , the product of the arcA gene , is known to repress the expression of many genes of E. coli that are not required for anaerobic growth ( 23 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1565612" target="_blank">1565612</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA represses anaerobic gene expression in E. coli ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996819" target="_blank">14996819</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was also concluded that any involvement of FNR must be indirect ( or operational only in the absence of ArcA ) , because a c n A expression was not enhanced in an fnr mutant , but it was partially repressed under aerobic conditions by fnr + amplification in an arcA + strain ( Gruer & Guest , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9421904" target="_blank">9421904</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been reported that FNR is able to sense oxygen directly ( 47 ) , while the ArcB/ArcA system responds to the content of the quinone pool ( 4 , 5 , 17 ) and switches on the expression of fermentation genes and represses aerobic pathways when E. coli encounters low-oxy-gen growth conditions ( 21 , 22 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20709841" target="_blank">20709841</a>]<br></li>
<li>This residual induction was imparted by ArcA , since no anaerobic induction occurred when expression from this mutant promoter derivative was examined in a strain that can not synthesize ArcA -LCB- Fig. 4C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>]<br></li>
<li>These include sev - ArcA because the anaerobic induction eral of the symbiotic N2-fixation genes of cyd expression is significantly re - ( fix ) , which are probably regulated by duced in an arcA mutant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1957353" target="_blank">1957353</a>]<br></li>
<li>not regulated by ArcA but expression is activated by a novel regulator , Arr , which responds to the presence of amino acids during anaerobic growth ( Green & Guest , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9308170" target="_blank">9308170</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cho and coworkers [ 12 ] initially used quantitative RT-PCR to assay regulation of fadL and fadD by FadR and ArcA under anaerobic conditions and reported that deletion of either arcA , fadR alone , or both arcA and fadR resulted in increased fadL expression by 34 - , 4 - or 69-fold , respectively , whereas fadD transcription increased 69 - , 4.5 - , and 84-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23029459" target="_blank">23029459</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA DIRECTLY BINDS TO MULTIPLE SITES AT THE gadE PROMOTER TO ACTIVATE THE EXPRESSION OF THE gadE-mdtEF Since ArcA and MnmE were identiﬁed as transcription activators of the gadE-mdtEF operon , we next asked how these two regulators activate gadE expression , i.e. , through which promoters these two regulators affect the transcription of the gadE-mdtEF operon under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , the lldPRD operon is proposed to be under the control of the global regulator ArcA , which binds to positions 14 to 3 with respect to the transcriptional start site , corresponding to the proposed P2 promoter , and represses the expression of this operon under anaerobic conditions ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18263722" target="_blank">18263722</a>]<br></li>
<li>3474 RESULTS AND DISCUSSION ArcA and FNR are required for complete anaerobic pfl operon expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1592804" target="_blank">1592804</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggested that anaerobic expression of the gadE-mdtEF operon is primarily regulated by ArcA in both log phase and stationary phase under anaerobic condition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA and AppY had no effect on PhyaA expression under aerobic conditions , as expected ( Fig. 1C ) , since ArcA is not active aerobically and since AppY is poorly expressed under these growth conditions ( 1 , 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with the notion that PhyaA expression is regulated by IscR repression aerobically and by ArcA and AppY antirepression of IscR anaerobically , PhyaA-lacZ expression levels in the absence of any transcription factors were similar under anaerobic and aerobic conditions ( Fig. 1A and C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA alone appears to slightly repress PhyaA under anaerobic conditions , since a strain containing deletions of appY and iscR ( ArcA ) showed an intermediate expression level ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>The residual anaerobic repression suggests that other regulators may either repress acnA under anaerobic conditions ( especially in the absence of ArcA ) or activate a c n A expression under aerobic conditions both in the presence and absence of ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , under anaerobic conditions , the expression of fadK is independent of FadR and ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16849788" target="_blank">16849788</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA , AppY , and IscR act combinatorially to control hyaA promoter expression levels under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other than its effect on the rpoS regulon , CsgD expression appears to regulate a subset of anaerobiosis-dependent genes , such as ompW and pﬂB , both induced in anaerobic conditions by FNR , either alone or in concert with ArcA ( 18 , 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this same report , FNR and IHF were reported to have roles as weak repressors under anaerobic conditions , and it was suggested that the effect of FNR may be indirect as a consequence of its role in regulating ArcA expression ( 30 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12754220" target="_blank">12754220</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , it was reported recently that ArcA and FNR repressed the expression of puuA when E. coli was grown under anaerobic conditions and that there are putative binding motifs of ArcA and FNR upstream of the open reading frame of puuA ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18495664" target="_blank">18495664</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rather , hya expression in S. enterica is regulated not by IscR or ArcA but , rather , by FNR under anaerobic conditions ( 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23065979" target="_blank">23065979</a>]<br></li>
<li>is repressed by FNR and stimulated by ArcA under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9230919" target="_blank">9230919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of cyd is thus stimulated by ArcA under microaerobic conditions and repressed by FNR unde anaerobic conditions , resulting in a maximal expression under microaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11931557" target="_blank">11931557</a>]<br></li>
<li>tpx has been reported to be negatively regulated by ArcA ( Kim et al , 1999 ) ; as regulation by ArcZ is also negative , this regulatory circuit would suggest interlocking mechanisms for keeping tpx expression relatively low under most conditions ; it would be transcriptionally repressed under anaerobic growth conditions by ArcA , and translationally repressed under aerobic conditions by ArcZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the gatZYABC operon , negatively controlled by CsgD ( 10 ) ( Table 2 ) is repressed by ArcA in anaerobic conditions ( 60 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of F ( glcD-lacZ ) in this genetic background was no longer repressed under fermentative conditions , indicating that ArcA acts as an anaerobic repressor of the glc operon ( Fig. 3B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9880556" target="_blank">9880556</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of arcZ is repressed by the aerobic/anaerobic-sensing ArcA -- ArcB two-component system under anaerobic conditions and adds translational regulation to the ArcA -- ArcB regulon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20683441" target="_blank">20683441</a>]<br></li>
<li>The bet promoters were repressed by ArcA under anaerobic growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626294" target="_blank">8626294</a>]<br></li>
<li>This operon is induced under an-aerobic conditions in the presence of formate or fumarate , repressed in the presence of nitrate , and requires acidic pH , ArcA , and AppY for optimal expression ( 12 , 21 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702328" target="_blank">14702328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the conditions of growth that minimize Dp also maximize hya expression , it is plausible that the hya response to pHe is at least partially mediated by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464194" target="_blank">10464194</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of ArcA and H-NS on induction of appY expression under oxygen-limiting conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8655536" target="_blank">8655536</a>]<br></li>
<li>Puri ® cation and phosphorylation of His6-ArcA The expression of His6-ArcA from plasmid pQE30ArcA , cotransformed with pREP4 into E. coli M15 , was induced with IPTG ( 5 lM ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10071223" target="_blank">10071223</a>]<br></li>
<li>The immediate response to anaerobiosis of the hydrogenase 1 operon and of the appY gene could be mediated by ArcA alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>The pfl operon is one of only a few whose expression is regulated positively in response to anaerobiosis by ArcA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7934836" target="_blank">7934836</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA sequences located upstream from the cydAB P1 promoter are bound in vitro by the two regulatory proteins implicated in the oxygen control of cydAB expression , Fnr and ArcA ( Lynch and Lin , 1996 ; Cotter et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123679" target="_blank">11123679</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dual pattern of hemA gene regulation by the Fnr and ArcA regulatory proteins is similar to that seen for the genes for cytochrome d oxidase in E. coli ( Table 3 ) , where Fnr functions to repress cydAB gene expression while ArcA somehow functions to activate their expression ( 6 , 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previously , ArcA and Fnr have been reported to suppress fumA expression under anaerobiosis , whereas fumC was repressed only by ArcA ( Fig. 7 ) ( Park and Gunsalus , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22752906" target="_blank">22752906</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , from the present study , it is apparent that Fnr and ArcA can act relatively independently of one another to negatively control icd expression ( Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9209047" target="_blank">9209047</a>]<br></li>
<li>In stationary phase , arcA expression is partly S dependent and ArcA contributes to S stabilization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16291649" target="_blank">16291649</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine whether ArcA-dependent Fnr repression of sodA was produced by Fnr activation of arcA transcription , we have investigated the effects of Fnr and ArcA on arcA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8022271" target="_blank">8022271</a>]<br></li>
<li>Anaerobic induction of operon expression is dependent on the ArcA and Fnr transcription factors ( 10 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>Aerobic expression was independent of ArcA and Fnr , but induction of cydDC by nitrate and nitrite was dependent on NarL and Fnr .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9335308" target="_blank">9335308</a>]<br></li>
<li>Remarkably , in an arcA mutant , expression was derepressed aerobically , indicating that ArcA and Fnr are both involved in regulating this promoter , even when upstream regulatory sequences are missing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rather , it appears that both ArcA and Fnr can regulate pﬂ expression under particular circumstances in aerobically grown cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>In strains defective in ArcA and Fnr synthesis , expression was reduced both aerobically and anaerobically .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665524" target="_blank">7665524</a>]<br></li>
<li>A similar relationship was recently observed for ArcA and Fnr control of cydAB operon expression in E. coli ( 6 , 10 ) Strain ( genotype ) + Oxygen - Oxygen During aerobic cell growth , expression in the arcA fnr double mutant was similar to that in the arcA strain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8071201" target="_blank">8071201</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sensor ± regulator pair , ArcB ± ArcA , is responsible for the microaerobic activation of the cydAB operon , whereas the anaerobic regulator Fnr represses its expression in the absence of oxygen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10998176" target="_blank">10998176</a>]<br></li>
<li>During anaerobic growth , both Fnr and ArcA act as repressors of cyo operon expression ( 12 , 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the expression of the cyd operon has been shown to be activated by ArcA during anaerobic as well as aerobic growth ( 25 ) and to be repressed by Fnr during anaerobic growth ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626281" target="_blank">8626281</a>]<br></li>
<li>To examine the effects of FNR and ArcA on expression of the E. coli nrdDG operon under oxic and anoxic conditions , Δfnr and ΔarcA mutations were individually transduced into -- -- strain IG40 to generate strains IG34 ( Fnr ) , IG35 ( ArcA ) , -- -- and IG36 ( Fnr / ArcA ) , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18683632" target="_blank">18683632</a>]<br></li>
